00:00:45.850 --> 00:00:47.510
- Hello, good afternoon.

00:00:47.510 --> 00:00:50.753
I'm John Campbell, a philosophy
professor here at Berkeley,

00:00:51.630 --> 00:00:52.880
and I'd like to welcome you

00:00:52.880 --> 00:00:56.553
to this rainy windswept Howison Lecture.

00:00:58.110 --> 00:01:02.270
George Howison was born in 1834.

00:01:02.270 --> 00:01:06.240
He really entered academic
life as a mathematics professor

00:01:06.240 --> 00:01:10.110
at the University of
Washington at St. Louis,

00:01:10.110 --> 00:01:14.250
so he began his academic life
as a mathematics professor

00:01:14.250 --> 00:01:17.210
but in St. Louis, he joined a group

00:01:17.210 --> 00:01:20.543
who were reading Hegel's
Phenomenology of Spirit.

00:01:22.240 --> 00:01:25.770
This was a rather
rambunctious, larger than life,

00:01:25.770 --> 00:01:28.983
collection of academic characters.

00:01:30.030 --> 00:01:34.633
The St. Louis Hegelians
were a very vibrant force.

00:01:35.480 --> 00:01:38.670
They were very engaged with
and ultimately swept away

00:01:38.670 --> 00:01:42.603
by the emerging naturalism
in American philosophy.

00:01:44.578 --> 00:01:45.411
Howison's legacy was
perhaps the most enduring

00:01:45.411 --> 00:01:49.290
of any of them.

00:01:49.290 --> 00:01:51.830
He seems to have had Josiah Royce,

00:01:51.830 --> 00:01:54.210
in particular, as his nemesis.

00:01:54.210 --> 00:01:56.090
Howison wrote:

00:01:56.090 --> 00:01:59.970
The most depressing sign
about Josiah Royce's thinking

00:01:59.970 --> 00:02:04.450
is that he seems perfectly aware
how this makes no provision

00:02:04.450 --> 00:02:08.340
either for immortality or for real freedom

00:02:08.340 --> 00:02:12.570
and yet he appears to have
no uneasiness under it

00:02:12.570 --> 00:02:16.810
but to contemplate this
ghastly destiny of ours

00:02:16.810 --> 00:02:21.180
with a complacency even
savoring of self-satisfaction.

00:02:21.180 --> 00:02:22.751
(audience laughing)

00:02:22.751 --> 00:02:24.933
Howison had a lot of gusto I think.

00:02:25.890 --> 00:02:28.720
He became the holder of
the first endowed chair

00:02:28.720 --> 00:02:30.217
in philosophy at Berkeley,

00:02:30.217 --> 00:02:33.450
and he built the philosophy department.

00:02:33.450 --> 00:02:38.450
He was evidently an influential
and much-loved individual,

00:02:38.470 --> 00:02:41.970
and on his death, his
friends and colleagues

00:02:41.970 --> 00:02:45.770
put together a fund that
is funding today's lecture

00:02:45.770 --> 00:02:48.160
to continue his work by bringing

00:02:48.160 --> 00:02:48.993
the most influential figures
of the day to speak here.

00:02:48.993 --> 00:02:49.826
And I think we really
couldn't have a better person

00:02:49.826 --> 00:02:54.700
to fill that role than
Professor Kwame Anthony Appiah.

00:03:00.860 --> 00:03:03.403
He's had many awards and honors.

00:03:04.480 --> 00:03:07.490
A representative sample
would be, for example,

00:03:07.490 --> 00:03:10.990
the National Humanities Medal,

00:03:10.990 --> 00:03:13.770
Forbes magazine put him on a list

00:03:13.770 --> 00:03:17.910
of the world's seven
most powerful thinkers.

00:03:17.910 --> 00:03:20.311
This is not usually what happens
to philosophy professors.

00:03:20.311 --> 00:03:21.970
(audience laughing)

00:03:21.970 --> 00:03:25.060
In his many books, he's challenged

00:03:25.060 --> 00:03:28.400
and engaged with questions
about identity and culture

00:03:28.400 --> 00:03:31.680
that matter to all of us every day.

00:03:31.680 --> 00:03:35.510
He said that we should live
with fractured identities,

00:03:35.510 --> 00:03:39.950
engage in identity play,
find solidarity, yes,

00:03:39.950 --> 00:03:44.950
but recognize contingency,
and above all practice irony.

00:03:45.710 --> 00:03:48.047
In a memorable passage, he said,

00:03:48.047 --> 00:03:51.787
"The truth is that there are no races.

00:03:51.787 --> 00:03:56.237
"There is nothing in the world
we can ask race to do for us.

00:03:56.237 --> 00:03:59.187
"As we've seen, even the biologists notion

00:03:59.187 --> 00:04:01.467
"has only limited uses,

00:04:01.467 --> 00:04:04.617
"and the notion that underlies
the more hateful racisms

00:04:04.617 --> 00:04:09.277
"of the modern era refers to
nothing in the world at all."

00:04:10.260 --> 00:04:14.440
But he's written across a
very wide range of subjects.

00:04:14.440 --> 00:04:15.273
His dissertation was in
probabilistic semantics,

00:04:15.273 --> 00:04:20.258
his first two books were
on philosophy of language.

00:04:21.350 --> 00:04:24.050
He's written three novels.

00:04:24.050 --> 00:04:26.260
It's been an extraordinary career

00:04:26.260 --> 00:04:28.570
covering a panorama of topics,

00:04:28.570 --> 00:04:32.760
and today we are privileged
to hear the latest direction

00:04:32.760 --> 00:04:35.850
of his current work,
which as I understand it,

00:04:35.850 --> 00:04:39.780
he's opening up the topic of idealization.

00:04:39.780 --> 00:04:44.770
So his lecture today is called
the Philosophy of "As If."

00:04:45.613 --> 00:04:48.168
Will you please join me in
welcoming Professor Appiah.

00:04:48.168 --> 00:04:51.251
(audience applauds)

00:04:54.491 --> 00:04:58.630
- Thank you.

00:04:58.630 --> 00:05:00.823
Thanks very much for
that kind introduction.

00:05:02.520 --> 00:05:03.362
Imagine you were raised in a devout

00:05:03.362 --> 00:05:08.362
Shui-Bian parsonage near
Tuebingen in the mid-19th century.

00:05:10.310 --> 00:05:11.940
That may be hard for some of you.

00:05:11.940 --> 00:05:13.790
And grew up with great respect

00:05:13.790 --> 00:05:16.270
for the leading theologians of your age.

00:05:16.270 --> 00:05:19.030
Imagine, too, that you had
the profoundest engagement

00:05:19.030 --> 00:05:23.130
with the ethical and aesthetic
aspects of Christianity.

00:05:23.130 --> 00:05:26.060
Suppose, finally, that you
became a serious student

00:05:26.060 --> 00:05:28.900
of Kant and Schopenhauer Nietzsche

00:05:28.900 --> 00:05:31.200
and that you moved in part as a result

00:05:31.200 --> 00:05:35.150
from theism, to pantheism, to agnosticism,

00:05:35.150 --> 00:05:35.983
while retaining your Christian ethical

00:05:35.983 --> 00:05:39.920
and aesthetic commitments.

00:05:39.920 --> 00:05:40.753
Then, since like all
educated men and women

00:05:40.753 --> 00:05:41.586
of your place and time, you were familiar

00:05:41.586 --> 00:05:46.586
with classical Greek and Roman ideas,

00:05:46.860 --> 00:05:49.500
you might come to feel, quote,

00:05:49.500 --> 00:05:52.800
according to the customs of
the cultured Greeks and Romans,

00:05:52.800 --> 00:05:56.610
one may regard and treat
these myths as myths

00:05:56.610 --> 00:05:59.340
and yet, or rather, just because of this

00:05:59.340 --> 00:06:02.290
continue to esteem such fictions

00:06:02.290 --> 00:06:04.533
for their ethical and aesthetic value.

00:06:05.720 --> 00:06:08.780
This was pretty much what
happened to Hans Vaihinger,

00:06:08.780 --> 00:06:10.710
the philosopher who wrote those words

00:06:10.710 --> 00:06:12.620
in his autobiographical essay,

00:06:12.620 --> 00:06:15.825
which preceded his 1911 magnum opus

00:06:15.825 --> 00:06:18.533
(speaking in foreign language)

00:06:18.533 --> 00:06:22.100
translated in 1924 into
English by CK Ogden

00:06:22.100 --> 00:06:25.197
as The Philosophy "of As If".

00:06:26.556 --> 00:06:29.950
Vaihinger tells us there,
that he breached the view

00:06:29.950 --> 00:06:33.630
that theology was composed
of, what he called, myths

00:06:33.630 --> 00:06:37.000
by his mid-20s, about the
time of his graduation

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:39.002
from the University of Tuebingen.

00:06:39.002 --> 00:06:40.730
Over the next 40 years as a student

00:06:40.730 --> 00:06:41.950
of the history of mathematics

00:06:41.950 --> 00:06:43.620
and the physic physical sciences

00:06:43.620 --> 00:06:46.204
and while keeping up with
the psychology of his day,

00:06:46.204 --> 00:06:48.880
Vaihinger came to apply the same strategy

00:06:48.880 --> 00:06:52.820
over and over again to
one field after another.

00:06:52.820 --> 00:06:57.820
Abandoning realism about a domain, atoms,

00:06:58.230 --> 00:07:01.460
infinitesimally, imaginary numbers, law,

00:07:01.460 --> 00:07:04.223
space, abstract objects, force,

00:07:05.180 --> 00:07:08.210
economics, freedom, the idea of freedom,

00:07:08.210 --> 00:07:10.870
but maintaining what he called his esteem,

00:07:10.870 --> 00:07:14.723
for the corresponding ideas
because of their utility.

00:07:15.570 --> 00:07:18.660
And in explicitly connecting
this strategy with the one

00:07:18.660 --> 00:07:20.910
that Kant had made famous in arguing

00:07:20.910 --> 00:07:25.230
that rational agency required
us to act as if we were free,

00:07:25.230 --> 00:07:27.130
even though our theoretical understanding

00:07:27.130 --> 00:07:29.488
showed that we were
governed by immutable laws,

00:07:29.488 --> 00:07:33.670
he claimed a Kantian
ancestry for his ideas.

00:07:33.670 --> 00:07:37.225
Indeed in the final section
of the philosophy of as if,

00:07:37.225 --> 00:07:41.060
Vaihinger records scores
of places in Kant's work

00:07:41.060 --> 00:07:43.940
where his great predecessor
speaks of proceeding

00:07:43.940 --> 00:07:48.373
as if what is theoretically
known to be false, is true.

00:07:50.640 --> 00:07:52.980
Vaihinger's suggestion that
large areas of our thought

00:07:52.980 --> 00:07:55.570
are fictions amounts to this.

00:07:55.570 --> 00:07:59.390
Very often we can reasonably proceed,

00:07:59.390 --> 00:08:02.560
as if what we know to be false, were true,

00:08:02.560 --> 00:08:06.280
because it's useful for
some purpose to do so.

00:08:06.280 --> 00:08:09.720
There were shades here
of pragmatism of course,

00:08:09.720 --> 00:08:12.930
on the first page of the
general introductory remarks

00:08:12.930 --> 00:08:16.120
on fictional constructs, Vaihinger wrote,

00:08:16.120 --> 00:08:19.010
it must be remembered, that
the object of the world

00:08:19.010 --> 00:08:23.430
of ideas as a whole, is not
the portrayal of reality,

00:08:23.430 --> 00:08:25.710
this would be an utterly impossible task

00:08:25.710 --> 00:08:28.870
but rather to provide an instrument

00:08:28.870 --> 00:08:32.503
for finding our way about
more easily in the world.

00:08:33.430 --> 00:08:35.670
Vaihinger proposed in essence

00:08:35.670 --> 00:08:38.910
that an idealization is a useful fiction.

00:08:38.910 --> 00:08:41.110
Or as he once put it that fictions are

00:08:41.110 --> 00:08:43.920
errors but fruitful errors.

00:08:43.920 --> 00:08:46.810
And for anyone interested in
this powerful way of thinking

00:08:46.810 --> 00:08:50.750
about idealization, Vaihinger
work is a treasure trove

00:08:50.750 --> 00:08:52.383
of interesting resources.

00:08:53.510 --> 00:08:55.420
But there's one way
which Vaihinger differs

00:08:55.420 --> 00:08:58.569
from at least one strand of pragmatism;

00:08:58.569 --> 00:09:02.154
he thinks that there's a
gap between what is true

00:09:02.154 --> 00:09:04.600
and what it is useful to believe.

00:09:04.600 --> 00:09:08.440
That's why he asserts that
most of our thought is fiction.

00:09:08.440 --> 00:09:11.280
If you equated the true
and the useful to believe

00:09:11.280 --> 00:09:13.490
as people say some pragmatists do,

00:09:13.490 --> 00:09:15.970
then you would lose exactly the contrast

00:09:15.970 --> 00:09:18.620
that guided the philosophy of 'As If'.

00:09:18.620 --> 00:09:20.730
And that book is the work
of a modern philosopher

00:09:20.730 --> 00:09:22.190
who thought long and hard about

00:09:22.190 --> 00:09:23.966
this particular tangle of ideas

00:09:23.966 --> 00:09:27.730
and thought about its application
over the widest range.

00:09:27.730 --> 00:09:30.620
Others may have gone
deeper into idealization

00:09:30.620 --> 00:09:32.920
in one sphere or another, but Vaihinger,

00:09:32.920 --> 00:09:35.800
is the first thinker I
know of who defined clearly

00:09:35.800 --> 00:09:38.523
the issues I'd like to come to grips with.

00:09:41.254 --> 00:09:44.610
Vaihinger's notion of what
he called a real fiction

00:09:44.610 --> 00:09:48.530
is I think in one way quite surprising.

00:09:48.530 --> 00:09:51.363
A real fiction he held,
involved a thought,

00:09:51.363 --> 00:09:56.363
that was not just false but
in some way contradictory.

00:09:57.450 --> 00:09:59.540
As he thought such useful ideas

00:09:59.540 --> 00:10:02.018
as the square root of a negative number

00:10:02.018 --> 00:10:05.600
or the atom were contradictory.

00:10:05.600 --> 00:10:07.750
On his view, when we understand the world

00:10:07.750 --> 00:10:10.310
as composed of atoms,
remember we are in the physics

00:10:10.310 --> 00:10:12.220
and chemistry of the late 19th century,

00:10:12.220 --> 00:10:15.890
we're supposing something
that we know to be impossible.

00:10:15.890 --> 00:10:18.440
Suppose quote, following
(speaks foreign language),

00:10:20.980 --> 00:10:24.197
a quartet of distinguished 19th
century physical scientists,

00:10:24.197 --> 00:10:26.187
"Suppose we designate the atoms

00:10:26.187 --> 00:10:29.327
"as centers without extension.

00:10:29.327 --> 00:10:31.047
"The result," he said,

00:10:31.047 --> 00:10:34.537
"turns out to be a very
strange construction indeed.

00:10:34.537 --> 00:10:38.027
"For an entity without extension
that is at the same time

00:10:38.027 --> 00:10:40.637
"a substantial bearer of forces,

00:10:40.637 --> 00:10:42.917
"that is simply a combination of words

00:10:42.917 --> 00:10:45.949
"with which no definite
meaning can be connected."

00:10:45.949 --> 00:10:49.100
Defining an atom as a point mass

00:10:49.100 --> 00:10:52.320
seems to require among
other things for example,

00:10:52.320 --> 00:10:55.270
that it should be, infinitely dense.

00:10:55.270 --> 00:10:57.720
What sense, Viahinger
makes one want to ask,

00:10:57.720 --> 00:10:59.543
can one make of that?

00:11:01.010 --> 00:11:03.150
Similarly, like many in
his day Viahinger thought

00:11:03.150 --> 00:11:05.686
there was something simply contradictory

00:11:05.686 --> 00:11:09.200
in the conception of the imaginary number,

00:11:09.200 --> 00:11:11.370
which Gauss had made
such successful use of

00:11:11.370 --> 00:11:13.550
in the early 19th century.

00:11:13.550 --> 00:11:15.870
Viahinger's view is nicely articulated

00:11:15.870 --> 00:11:18.840
in a famous conversation
in Robert Musil's novel,

00:11:18.840 --> 00:11:22.295
Die Verwirrungen des Zöglings Törless.

00:11:22.295 --> 00:11:24.000
There he describes a conversation

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:26.930
between Törless, the
protagonist and a friend

00:11:26.930 --> 00:11:29.050
about imaginary numbers.

00:11:29.050 --> 00:11:32.130
Törless objects that quote,
this is my translation,

00:11:32.130 --> 00:11:33.830
you wouldn't like to hear
me read it in the German.

00:11:33.830 --> 00:11:37.453
Törless objects that quote,
there is no such thing,

00:11:37.453 --> 00:11:40.490
any number, whether it's
positive or negative

00:11:40.490 --> 00:11:43.030
yield something positive
when it's squared,

00:11:43.030 --> 00:11:45.410
so there can't be a bonafide number.

00:11:45.410 --> 00:11:48.040
That's the square root
of something negative.

00:11:48.040 --> 00:11:52.090
But Törless insists, what's
remarkable, is precisely,

00:11:52.090 --> 00:11:55.170
one can really do calculations
with such imaginary

00:11:55.170 --> 00:11:57.100
or otherwise impossible values

00:11:57.100 --> 00:12:00.470
and end up with a tangible result.

00:12:00.470 --> 00:12:02.640
Or as Viahinger puts it in one of his

00:12:02.640 --> 00:12:04.540
characteristic paradoxes,

00:12:04.540 --> 00:12:08.683
the concept in question is
contradictory but necessary.

00:12:09.918 --> 00:12:12.708
Viahinger contrasted these real fictions

00:12:12.708 --> 00:12:16.970
with what he called semi-fictions
where the concepts quote,

00:12:16.970 --> 00:12:19.840
Only contradict reality is
given or deviate from it

00:12:19.840 --> 00:12:22.493
but are not in themselves contradictory.

00:12:23.710 --> 00:12:26.280
One clear example he gives would be

00:12:26.280 --> 00:12:29.140
Adam Smith's rational egoism.

00:12:29.140 --> 00:12:32.430
Which Viahinger understands
as an assumption

00:12:32.430 --> 00:12:34.460
that Smith knew to be false.

00:12:34.460 --> 00:12:36.570
But which nevertheless allowed
the Scottish philosopher

00:12:36.570 --> 00:12:40.040
to construct a useful
predictive economics.

00:12:40.040 --> 00:12:43.320
Quote, the empirical
manifestations of human actions

00:12:43.320 --> 00:12:45.840
are so excessively complicated,

00:12:45.840 --> 00:12:48.000
that they present almost
insuperable obstacles

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:49.940
when we try to understand
them theoretically

00:12:49.940 --> 00:12:52.804
and reduce them to causal factors.

00:12:52.804 --> 00:12:55.855
For the construction of his
system of political economy

00:12:55.855 --> 00:12:59.150
this is still Viahinger, it
was essential for Adam Smith

00:12:59.150 --> 00:13:01.141
to interpret human activity causally.

00:13:01.141 --> 00:13:03.182
With unerring instinct he realized,

00:13:03.182 --> 00:13:05.700
that the main cause lay in egoism

00:13:05.700 --> 00:13:08.240
and he formulated his
assumption in such a way

00:13:08.240 --> 00:13:10.330
that all human actions, and particularly

00:13:10.330 --> 00:13:13.540
those of a business or
political economical nature,

00:13:13.540 --> 00:13:15.660
could be looked upon as if

00:13:15.660 --> 00:13:19.010
their driving force lay
in one factor, egoism.

00:13:19.010 --> 00:13:22.630
Thus, all subsidiary causes
and partially-conditional

00:13:22.630 --> 00:13:25.700
factors such as goodwill,
habit and so forth,

00:13:25.700 --> 00:13:27.720
are here neglected.

00:13:27.720 --> 00:13:31.134
With the aid of this
abstract cause, Adam Smith

00:13:31.134 --> 00:13:34.462
succeeded in bringing the
whole of political economy

00:13:34.462 --> 00:13:36.323
into an ordered system.

00:13:37.820 --> 00:13:38.653
Nevertheless Viahinger
went on to argue, these,

00:13:38.653 --> 00:13:43.265
quote, 'provisional assumptions'
are or at least should be,

00:13:43.265 --> 00:13:45.166
accompanied by the consciousness

00:13:45.166 --> 00:13:48.170
that they do not correspond to reality

00:13:48.170 --> 00:13:50.290
and that they deliberate they substitute

00:13:50.290 --> 00:13:53.070
a fraction of reality,
for the complete range

00:13:53.070 --> 00:13:55.023
of causes and effects.

00:13:57.220 --> 00:13:59.170
Now the difficulty with Viahinger's idea

00:13:59.170 --> 00:14:00.520
of the contradictory fiction,

00:14:00.520 --> 00:14:03.880
of the model that's literally
inconsistent is obvious.

00:14:03.880 --> 00:14:05.570
It makes it very hard to understand

00:14:05.570 --> 00:14:08.690
how an idealization can be useful,

00:14:08.690 --> 00:14:12.651
since, as we teach our
students in introductory logic

00:14:12.651 --> 00:14:15.440
if a theory is inconsistent
we can deduce from it

00:14:15.440 --> 00:14:17.210
anything at all.

00:14:17.210 --> 00:14:19.180
And the prediction that
something will happen

00:14:19.180 --> 00:14:22.050
and that it won't happen,
can't surely be useful,

00:14:22.050 --> 00:14:23.850
indeed it's not really a prediction.

00:14:24.950 --> 00:14:28.694
Of course, one can construct
paraconsistent logics

00:14:28.694 --> 00:14:31.500
in which the general thesis
that from a contradiction

00:14:31.500 --> 00:14:33.880
anything follows, fails.

00:14:33.880 --> 00:14:35.720
But I suspect that the way that many

00:14:35.720 --> 00:14:39.280
of our actual inconsistencies
are actually corralled in,

00:14:39.280 --> 00:14:42.290
is not by the implementation
of a non-standard logic,

00:14:42.290 --> 00:14:44.965
but by what you might
call functional isolation,

00:14:44.965 --> 00:14:48.830
so that in effect we have a
large set of families of beliefs

00:14:48.830 --> 00:14:50.830
each of which we try to keep consistent

00:14:50.830 --> 00:14:53.070
and these families aren't
usually brought together

00:14:53.070 --> 00:14:54.870
in deliberation so the contradictions

00:14:54.870 --> 00:14:56.170
are as it were kept apart.

00:14:57.210 --> 00:14:59.240
David Lewis the philosopher
once exemplified

00:14:59.240 --> 00:15:01.150
this sort of thing in a nice way,

00:15:01.150 --> 00:15:04.210
in a story about how he
failed for a while to notice

00:15:04.210 --> 00:15:06.720
that he acted as if a
certain Street in Princeton

00:15:06.720 --> 00:15:09.668
was parallel to the railway
track for some purposes

00:15:09.668 --> 00:15:12.403
and orthogonal to it for other purposes.

00:15:15.170 --> 00:15:17.120
In Euclidean space that's not possible.

00:15:17.970 --> 00:15:20.070
Now, everybody has experiences

00:15:20.070 --> 00:15:22.803
of the inconsistency
of such internal maps.

00:15:23.920 --> 00:15:25.300
Some of our colleagues working

00:15:25.300 --> 00:15:27.530
in the philosophy of
science have suggested,

00:15:27.530 --> 00:15:30.210
that scientific explanations
in contemporary physics

00:15:30.210 --> 00:15:32.900
do involve mathematically
inconsistent theories

00:15:32.900 --> 00:15:34.726
or to speak more carefully,

00:15:34.726 --> 00:15:37.590
involve the application at the same time

00:15:37.590 --> 00:15:40.720
of models that are
inconsistent with each other,

00:15:40.720 --> 00:15:43.400
even of each of them is itself consistent.

00:15:43.400 --> 00:15:46.360
Actually using these theories
involves in effect then,

00:15:46.360 --> 00:15:49.600
knowing which lines of
inference one should

00:15:49.600 --> 00:15:52.460
and which one should not follow.

00:15:52.460 --> 00:15:54.070
Nancy Cartwright for example,

00:15:54.070 --> 00:15:57.110
has criticized what she
calls the vending machine

00:15:57.110 --> 00:16:00.790
model of theories, in which you
feed in certain I'm quoting,

00:16:00.790 --> 00:16:03.610
certain prescribed forms
for the desire output,

00:16:03.610 --> 00:16:06.930
it gurgitates for a
while, then it drops out

00:16:06.930 --> 00:16:10.020
the sort for representation,
plunk on the tray

00:16:10.020 --> 00:16:12.703
fully formed as Athena
from the brain of Zeus.

00:16:14.537 --> 00:16:17.107
"I'd rather," she argues,
"the process involves

00:16:17.107 --> 00:16:18.547
"knowing how to take advantage

00:16:18.547 --> 00:16:20.637
"of the available formal resources,

00:16:20.637 --> 00:16:23.023
"to treat a specific phenomenon."

00:16:23.023 --> 00:16:25.410
If she's right, then Viahinger's idea

00:16:25.410 --> 00:16:28.170
that idea our idealizations
are contradictory,

00:16:28.170 --> 00:16:31.310
may turn out, in a way, to be correct.

00:16:31.310 --> 00:16:33.410
But that's because the
understanding of the world

00:16:33.410 --> 00:16:35.370
implicit in the scientific theory,

00:16:35.370 --> 00:16:37.600
the knowledge it delivers, is held,

00:16:37.600 --> 00:16:40.460
not just in the abstract
statement of the theory

00:16:40.460 --> 00:16:42.614
but in the skill of applying it

00:16:42.614 --> 00:16:45.664
to certain standard cases in particular,

00:16:45.664 --> 00:16:47.810
sorry in certain standard cases,

00:16:47.810 --> 00:16:50.890
in particular to what Cartwright
calls ontological machine,

00:16:50.890 --> 00:16:53.520
not sorry, nomological machines,

00:16:53.520 --> 00:16:55.868
where a nomological
machine is as she says,

00:16:55.868 --> 00:16:59.577
"A fixed enough arrangement
of components or factors,

00:16:59.577 --> 00:17:02.147
"with stable enough
capacities that in the right

00:17:02.147 --> 00:17:03.887
"sort of stable enough environment

00:17:03.887 --> 00:17:05.547
"will with repeated operation,

00:17:05.547 --> 00:17:08.207
"give rise to the kind of regular behavior

00:17:08.207 --> 00:17:10.653
"that we represent in our scientific laws.

00:17:11.587 --> 00:17:13.300
"A nomological machine,"

00:17:13.300 --> 00:17:17.027
she gives the solar system as one example,

00:17:17.027 --> 00:17:19.847
"is screened off enough
from outside forces

00:17:19.847 --> 00:17:23.590
"that we can make roughly
reliable laws about its motions."

00:17:23.590 --> 00:17:25.420
So the physicists knowledge is not held

00:17:25.420 --> 00:17:28.360
in the formal theory,
which is one reason why

00:17:28.360 --> 00:17:30.903
it's inconsistency should worry us less.

00:17:32.061 --> 00:17:33.900
I don't know enough about
the relevant physics

00:17:33.900 --> 00:17:36.360
to evaluate many of these claims,

00:17:36.360 --> 00:17:38.390
but they surely do support the idea

00:17:38.390 --> 00:17:41.163
that Viahinger was right
about something important.

00:17:42.110 --> 00:17:43.770
You can't refute the idea

00:17:43.770 --> 00:17:45.910
that our best theories are inconsistent,

00:17:45.910 --> 00:17:49.102
by arguing that the world
itself can't be inconsistent

00:17:49.102 --> 00:17:52.080
unless you presuppose
that our best theories,

00:17:52.080 --> 00:17:54.183
aim only at truth.

00:17:55.730 --> 00:17:57.690
There's a point here of some importance,

00:17:57.690 --> 00:17:59.653
even if it may prove controversial.

00:18:00.770 --> 00:18:03.246
Once we grant that our
models assume what is not so,

00:18:03.246 --> 00:18:07.187
the fact that another
representation is inconsistent

00:18:07.187 --> 00:18:09.570
with the model we currently accept,

00:18:09.570 --> 00:18:14.190
cannot by itself count,
against accepting it too.

00:18:14.190 --> 00:18:18.100
For we know, ex hypothesi,
that we already have a picture

00:18:18.100 --> 00:18:22.280
that is untrue to how
things strictly speaking are

00:18:22.280 --> 00:18:23.700
and the success of our current model

00:18:23.700 --> 00:18:24.960
for some purpose or other,

00:18:24.960 --> 00:18:27.410
cannot count against
accepting another model

00:18:27.410 --> 00:18:31.350
that is inconsistent with
it, for at least two reasons.

00:18:31.350 --> 00:18:34.150
One, is that just because our theory,

00:18:34.150 --> 00:18:36.627
which is not strictly true,

00:18:36.627 --> 00:18:40.480
succeeds to some degree for some purpose.

00:18:40.480 --> 00:18:43.730
We cannot infer that another
theory inconsistent with it

00:18:43.730 --> 00:18:46.740
could not also succeed, to
more or less the same degree

00:18:46.740 --> 00:18:48.320
for the same purpose?

00:18:48.320 --> 00:18:51.890
And the other is that, what is
successful for some purposes,

00:18:51.890 --> 00:18:53.903
may not be successful for others.

00:18:54.780 --> 00:18:57.870
The result is that Viahinger
can give us an explanation

00:18:57.870 --> 00:19:01.327
for why we might profit from
mobilizing a set of theories

00:19:01.327 --> 00:19:04.053
that are inconsistent with one another.

00:19:05.170 --> 00:19:07.807
Another of Vaihinger distinctions

00:19:07.807 --> 00:19:10.150
between what he called fictions

00:19:10.150 --> 00:19:12.670
and what he called hypotheses is,

00:19:12.670 --> 00:19:15.220
surely uncontroversially helpful.

00:19:15.220 --> 00:19:18.403
Viahinger's point was
at the very same claim,

00:19:18.403 --> 00:19:22.189
Adam Smith's claim say that
men are rational egoists,

00:19:22.189 --> 00:19:26.850
could be treated either as a
fiction, a fruitful untruth

00:19:26.850 --> 00:19:28.800
or as something whose actual truth

00:19:28.800 --> 00:19:31.579
remains an open possibility.

00:19:31.579 --> 00:19:34.320
And a good deal of Viahinger's
argument demands to saying,

00:19:34.320 --> 00:19:37.240
that many theories that
are offered as hypotheses,

00:19:37.240 --> 00:19:39.057
need not be given up
because some of their claims

00:19:39.057 --> 00:19:42.710
are known to be false, because
we can continue with them,

00:19:42.710 --> 00:19:45.063
treating them now as fictions.

00:19:46.550 --> 00:19:49.830
But if idealization is Viahinger proposed

00:19:49.830 --> 00:19:52.460
the question of useful untruths,

00:19:52.460 --> 00:19:55.280
there are now two questions
to ask that are familiar

00:19:55.280 --> 00:19:57.300
from the discussions of pragmatist ideas

00:19:57.300 --> 00:19:59.760
about what it is useful to believe.

00:19:59.760 --> 00:20:02.240
First, useful for what?

00:20:02.240 --> 00:20:05.166
And second, if a falsehood is useful,

00:20:05.166 --> 00:20:08.130
isn't there some truth in the vicinity

00:20:08.130 --> 00:20:09.870
that would be even more useful?

00:20:09.870 --> 00:20:11.710
Why stick with the useful and truth?

00:20:11.710 --> 00:20:14.125
Won't the truth always be better?

00:20:14.125 --> 00:20:16.420
And I'll return to that second line

00:20:16.420 --> 00:20:18.340
of questioning in a
moment, but for the moment

00:20:18.340 --> 00:20:22.323
let's stick with the
first, useful for what?

00:20:23.513 --> 00:20:26.270
One old line of thought
here, it's a thought

00:20:26.270 --> 00:20:29.110
almost as old as systematic
philosophy in the West,

00:20:29.110 --> 00:20:33.490
is that utility means usefulness
in saving the phenomena.

00:20:33.490 --> 00:20:35.880
Simplifying idealization is useful,

00:20:35.880 --> 00:20:38.330
if it allows us to cover the past record

00:20:38.330 --> 00:20:40.780
and predict the future
course of our experiences.

00:20:41.744 --> 00:20:44.460
But despite some passages
that suggest this picture,

00:20:44.460 --> 00:20:46.600
I don't think this is Viahinger's view.

00:20:46.600 --> 00:20:50.510
What he thought, as I've
essentially already pointed out,

00:20:50.510 --> 00:20:52.750
was that it was in controlling the world

00:20:52.750 --> 00:20:54.900
that thought proved itself useful,

00:20:54.900 --> 00:20:57.980
our representations prove
themselves useful, and even though

00:20:57.980 --> 00:21:00.760
sensation is our only means
of access to the world,

00:21:00.760 --> 00:21:04.995
thoughts object is not to
manufacture or predict sensations

00:21:04.995 --> 00:21:09.070
but to control the world
that produces them.

00:21:09.070 --> 00:21:11.390
Viahinger's treatment
has the great virtue,

00:21:11.390 --> 00:21:13.930
that it responds in
regards questions about

00:21:13.930 --> 00:21:15.960
our everyday thinking about the world,

00:21:15.960 --> 00:21:18.297
that's continuous with
our scientific thinking.

00:21:18.297 --> 00:21:20.757
"Both aim," he says,
"at controlling reality,

00:21:20.757 --> 00:21:23.917
"both leave things out, in
order to make it practicable

00:21:23.917 --> 00:21:26.617
"to represent the world
we're trying to control."

00:21:27.950 --> 00:21:29.640
So Viahinger believes our representations

00:21:29.640 --> 00:21:32.630
are fundamentally tools that
allow us to control the world,

00:21:32.630 --> 00:21:35.453
but why must they be idealized?

00:21:36.537 --> 00:21:39.922
Let's begin by extamining a
passage Viahinger refers to

00:21:39.922 --> 00:21:42.880
in once more, a 19th century discussion

00:21:42.880 --> 00:21:45.320
of Adam Smith's idealizations
which we've already

00:21:45.320 --> 00:21:46.270
been talking about.

00:21:49.800 --> 00:21:52.330
He's quoting here Henry
Thomas Buckle's introduction

00:21:52.330 --> 00:21:54.580
to The History of Civilization in England.

00:21:54.580 --> 00:21:58.117
"Adam Smith in his Wealth of Nations,

00:21:58.117 --> 00:22:00.257
"simplified the study of human nature

00:22:00.257 --> 00:22:04.527
"by curtailing it of all its sympathy.

00:22:04.527 --> 00:22:07.207
"But," he continued, "this
most comprehensive thinker

00:22:07.207 --> 00:22:09.757
"was careful in his Theory
Of the Moral Sentiments

00:22:09.757 --> 00:22:11.767
"to restore the human nature,

00:22:11.767 --> 00:22:13.607
"the quality of which
the wealth of patience

00:22:13.607 --> 00:22:14.827
"had deprived it.

00:22:14.827 --> 00:22:17.927
"And thus by establishing two
different lines of argument,

00:22:17.927 --> 00:22:20.400
"he embraced the whole subject."

00:22:20.400 --> 00:22:23.920
Now, Buckle is overreaching
here for the complete treatment

00:22:23.920 --> 00:22:26.710
would presumably include
not just egoism and sympathy

00:22:26.710 --> 00:22:28.780
but all the psychological factors relevant

00:22:28.780 --> 00:22:30.700
for explaining human behavior.

00:22:30.700 --> 00:22:33.040
And as is clear from the
passage I cited earlier,

00:22:33.040 --> 00:22:34.653
one of Vaihinger's insights is that

00:22:34.653 --> 00:22:38.236
it's precisely the difficulty
of embracing the whole subject

00:22:38.236 --> 00:22:42.870
that makes idealization
inescapable on his view.

00:22:42.870 --> 00:22:44.260
It's the fact that the phenomena

00:22:44.260 --> 00:22:46.520
are an excessively complicated

00:22:46.520 --> 00:22:49.770
that requires us to leave
out some of the details.

00:22:49.770 --> 00:22:52.620
But to say that the
complexity is excessive,

00:22:52.620 --> 00:22:55.000
is to make a point not
so much about the world

00:22:55.000 --> 00:22:58.690
as about our capacity to understand it.

00:22:58.690 --> 00:23:02.030
The complexities exceed
our cognitive capacity

00:23:02.030 --> 00:23:05.577
to encompass them and this
is a fact as much about us

00:23:05.577 --> 00:23:07.043
as about them.

00:23:07.043 --> 00:23:09.410
Suppose for example
that the quantum theory

00:23:09.410 --> 00:23:10.683
were precisely true,

00:23:14.150 --> 00:23:16.183
in (scoffs) sorry.

00:23:17.130 --> 00:23:20.078
That may stretch your
imaginative capacities,

00:23:20.078 --> 00:23:21.930
it certainly stretches mine.

00:23:21.930 --> 00:23:24.880
In principle, I suppose
that would allow us to write

00:23:24.880 --> 00:23:27.543
a precise equation for each
of the atoms in a baseball.

00:23:27.543 --> 00:23:30.200
To describe the baseball we would then

00:23:30.200 --> 00:23:32.300
have to solve a system of
the order of something like

00:23:32.300 --> 00:23:34.680
10 to the 26 equations.

00:23:34.680 --> 00:23:37.246
No human being, I suggest,
knows how to do this,

00:23:37.246 --> 00:23:40.057
no machine exists that could do it either

00:23:40.057 --> 00:23:42.190
and even if there were such a machine,

00:23:42.190 --> 00:23:44.743
what an earth use would it be to us?

00:23:45.890 --> 00:23:47.940
If the utility of scientific fiction

00:23:47.940 --> 00:23:50.930
derives from the excessive
complexity of the world

00:23:50.930 --> 00:23:53.320
that is from the fact that
its complexity exceeds

00:23:53.320 --> 00:23:54.923
our cognitive capacities,

00:23:56.040 --> 00:23:58.370
the utility of religious
myth for Viahinger

00:23:58.370 --> 00:24:00.900
seems to come from somewhere else.

00:24:00.900 --> 00:24:04.230
He pronounces himself here a
disciple of Friedrich Langer

00:24:04.230 --> 00:24:07.324
who had articulated a
standpoint of the ideal

00:24:07.324 --> 00:24:09.850
that permits a metaphysical atheist,

00:24:09.850 --> 00:24:11.720
nevertheless to hold
on to religion as myth

00:24:11.720 --> 00:24:13.090
because of what he calls the

00:24:13.090 --> 00:24:16.400
ethical efficacy of religious language.

00:24:16.400 --> 00:24:20.250
Viahanger did not think atheists
couldn't have moral ideas,

00:24:20.250 --> 00:24:21.960
he did not think that if God was dead

00:24:21.960 --> 00:24:23.250
everything was permitted

00:24:23.250 --> 00:24:25.620
but he did think that we
more likely to be able

00:24:25.620 --> 00:24:28.820
to live by our ideals, if we express them

00:24:28.820 --> 00:24:32.620
poetically as it were,
in religious language.

00:24:32.620 --> 00:24:33.860
This is meant so far as I can see,

00:24:33.860 --> 00:24:35.790
is an empirical claim.

00:24:35.790 --> 00:24:37.580
And I'm not going to canvas the evidence

00:24:37.580 --> 00:24:39.041
for or against it here.

00:24:39.041 --> 00:24:41.850
Richard Braithwaite, one
of my earliest teachers

00:24:41.850 --> 00:24:43.930
in philosophy, argued later,

00:24:43.930 --> 00:24:46.380
that one could understand
and adopt religious belief

00:24:46.380 --> 00:24:48.210
without an appeal to theology,

00:24:48.210 --> 00:24:50.830
in effect, he thought, one could treat

00:24:50.830 --> 00:24:52.665
the Creed he recited on Sundays,

00:24:52.665 --> 00:24:55.060
explicitly as fiction.

00:24:55.060 --> 00:24:58.390
And Viahinger's treatment,
certainty of argument

00:24:58.390 --> 00:25:01.170
shows that the utility of
fictions can be conceived

00:25:01.170 --> 00:25:02.910
not only in their power to aid us

00:25:02.910 --> 00:25:04.571
in manipulating the world outside us,

00:25:04.571 --> 00:25:09.571
but also in their capacity
to help us manage ourselves.

00:25:09.770 --> 00:25:11.580
His thought like Kant's thought about

00:25:11.580 --> 00:25:13.510
the inevitability of the idea of freedom

00:25:13.510 --> 00:25:15.120
in the world of the understanding,

00:25:15.120 --> 00:25:17.045
is that we can grasp theoretically,

00:25:17.045 --> 00:25:19.330
that the ideas we're using a false,

00:25:19.330 --> 00:25:22.490
while still finding
them practically useful

00:25:22.490 --> 00:25:24.997
indeed, inescapable.

00:25:24.997 --> 00:25:28.245
So I suppose with Viahinger
that useful means,

00:25:28.245 --> 00:25:33.245
useful for managing the world
including sometimes ourselves.

00:25:33.374 --> 00:25:37.246
Then there's a puzzle about how
we can make good predictions

00:25:37.246 --> 00:25:39.736
by leaving stuff out.

00:25:39.736 --> 00:25:42.790
Vaihinger's answer I think,
first answer I think,

00:25:42.790 --> 00:25:46.860
can be twofold; first,
sometimes leaving stuff out

00:25:46.860 --> 00:25:48.620
makes too little difference to matter

00:25:48.620 --> 00:25:50.060
for the purpose at hand,

00:25:50.060 --> 00:25:52.930
as when we use the Newtonian
rather than Einstein

00:25:52.930 --> 00:25:54.630
in mechanics in building a bridge.

00:25:55.720 --> 00:25:57.103
This is a very familiar thought

00:25:57.103 --> 00:26:00.180
and the example is a familiar example.

00:26:00.180 --> 00:26:01.889
But Vaihinger also thought,

00:26:01.889 --> 00:26:04.919
the question had a second
more interesting answer,

00:26:04.919 --> 00:26:09.160
sometimes our idealizations
allow us to get things right

00:26:09.160 --> 00:26:12.324
because we proceed as
it were in two steps.

00:26:12.324 --> 00:26:15.120
First, ignoring a range of phenomena

00:26:15.120 --> 00:26:17.530
in order to build a model
of a world without them

00:26:17.530 --> 00:26:20.500
and then once we've grasped
how that model works,

00:26:20.500 --> 00:26:23.760
adding more and more of
the world gradually back in

00:26:23.760 --> 00:26:28.126
as he puts it, "If in fictions
thought contradicts reality,

00:26:28.126 --> 00:26:30.006
"or if it even contradicts itself

00:26:30.006 --> 00:26:32.947
"and in spite of this
questionable procedure,

00:26:32.947 --> 00:26:36.640
"it nevertheless succeeds in
corresponding to reality then,"

00:26:36.640 --> 00:26:38.407
and this is a necessary inference,

00:26:38.407 --> 00:26:41.177
"this deviation must have been corrected

00:26:41.177 --> 00:26:44.447
"and the contradiction
must have been made good."

00:26:45.640 --> 00:26:48.710
Viahinger was in the end,
something of an instrumentalist

00:26:48.710 --> 00:26:49.680
about theory.

00:26:49.680 --> 00:26:52.180
He focused as we've seen
on the role of our theories

00:26:52.180 --> 00:26:53.910
in controlling the world.

00:26:53.910 --> 00:26:56.180
But this line of thinking adamanted here,

00:26:56.180 --> 00:26:57.770
might suggest another view,

00:26:57.770 --> 00:27:00.440
in which we take the role
of the idealized model

00:27:00.440 --> 00:27:03.220
as helping us not just
or not even to predict

00:27:03.220 --> 00:27:07.160
or control the world,
but to understand it.

00:27:07.160 --> 00:27:09.408
That is a really important idea I think,

00:27:09.408 --> 00:27:13.790
I have only time here however
to note it and march on.

00:27:13.790 --> 00:27:16.750
And you know, when I finish
the book on this topic

00:27:16.750 --> 00:27:17.913
I will say more about that question

00:27:17.913 --> 00:27:21.043
but I'm going to mark it here
is an important possibility.

00:27:22.090 --> 00:27:23.750
'Cause I wanted now to discuss a second,

00:27:23.750 --> 00:27:26.340
more recent philosopher,

00:27:26.340 --> 00:27:29.040
first because his work can
be taken as a case study

00:27:29.040 --> 00:27:31.380
of Viahinger's philosophy of the 'as if',

00:27:31.380 --> 00:27:32.540
and second because in the course

00:27:32.540 --> 00:27:34.130
of thinking about his proposals,

00:27:34.130 --> 00:27:36.900
we can come to see the
power of Viahinger's picture

00:27:36.900 --> 00:27:40.376
in framing our understanding
of idealization.

00:27:40.376 --> 00:27:43.710
The philosopher I have in
mind is Daniel Dennett,

00:27:43.710 --> 00:27:46.157
who has urged us to adopt what he calls,

00:27:46.157 --> 00:27:48.870
"the intentional stance" to many things,

00:27:48.870 --> 00:27:52.260
ourselves among them and to
adopt "the design stance"

00:27:52.260 --> 00:27:55.993
to many things too,
ourselves included as well.

00:27:57.210 --> 00:28:00.010
To adopt the intentional
stance towards something,

00:28:00.010 --> 00:28:04.350
is to treat it or her as if
she were a rational agent

00:28:04.350 --> 00:28:06.120
with beliefs and desires,

00:28:06.120 --> 00:28:08.070
the beliefs and desires it ought to have

00:28:08.070 --> 00:28:10.650
given its place in the
world and its purpose,

00:28:10.650 --> 00:28:13.530
and then to predict what
this rational agent will do

00:28:13.530 --> 00:28:16.190
in order to further its goals.

00:28:16.190 --> 00:28:19.790
Similarly, to adopt the design
stance towards organisms

00:28:19.790 --> 00:28:21.370
and the things they produce,

00:28:21.370 --> 00:28:23.130
is to treat them as if they were designed

00:28:23.130 --> 00:28:25.130
to perform certain functions

00:28:25.130 --> 00:28:27.813
and this can allow us to
predict what they will do,

00:28:27.813 --> 00:28:31.475
just as we explain what it is
to be an intentional system

00:28:31.475 --> 00:28:34.410
by specifying the intentional stance,

00:28:34.410 --> 00:28:36.961
so we can say what it is
to have a certain function

00:28:36.961 --> 00:28:39.070
by adopting the design stance,

00:28:39.070 --> 00:28:41.350
by treating something
as if it had been made

00:28:41.350 --> 00:28:43.693
by a designer with certain aims.

00:28:44.647 --> 00:28:47.890
In each case, adopting
a stance of this sort

00:28:47.890 --> 00:28:51.445
involves treating something
as if something were so,

00:28:51.445 --> 00:28:54.540
as if it had internal
states of belief and desire,

00:28:54.540 --> 00:28:57.380
as if it were the product
of intentional design.

00:28:57.380 --> 00:29:02.130
So Dennett too as I say, is
a philosopher of the 'as if'.

00:29:02.130 --> 00:29:04.166
I've been arguing with Viahinger,

00:29:04.166 --> 00:29:07.920
that we do this a whole
lot in many domains,

00:29:07.920 --> 00:29:09.273
Dennett agrees.

00:29:10.840 --> 00:29:13.540
But that this is what we
are doing leads laterally

00:29:13.540 --> 00:29:16.299
back to the question why it works.

00:29:16.299 --> 00:29:18.860
If it works, I've suggested we have reason

00:29:18.860 --> 00:29:20.770
to go along with it, even perhaps

00:29:20.770 --> 00:29:22.370
at the price of inconsistency.

00:29:22.370 --> 00:29:24.040
That is what Nancy Cartwright taught me

00:29:24.040 --> 00:29:25.390
about much physics.

00:29:25.390 --> 00:29:28.150
It's what Viahinger
thought about theology,

00:29:28.150 --> 00:29:30.460
number theory, physics and economics,

00:29:30.460 --> 00:29:33.400
it's what Braithwaite thought
about religious language.

00:29:33.400 --> 00:29:38.240
But showing that it does
work, doesn't explain why.

00:29:38.240 --> 00:29:40.487
Cartwright believes, that it works

00:29:40.487 --> 00:29:43.300
because our theories latch
on to what she calls,

00:29:43.300 --> 00:29:45.972
the real capacities of much of the world.

00:29:45.972 --> 00:29:47.856
As far as I know she's right.

00:29:47.856 --> 00:29:50.369
But I want now to explore the question,

00:29:50.369 --> 00:29:53.210
why idealization works,
by thinking through

00:29:53.210 --> 00:29:55.920
some of Daniel Dennett's
insistence on the importance

00:29:55.920 --> 00:29:58.753
of the as if in the case of the mind.

00:30:00.710 --> 00:30:04.410
Dennett claims at least sometimes,

00:30:04.410 --> 00:30:06.640
that beliefs, but I've
already given you reason

00:30:06.640 --> 00:30:08.670
for not worrying too
much about inconsistency,

00:30:08.670 --> 00:30:10.370
so I won't point out
that another occasions

00:30:10.370 --> 00:30:11.800
he says the opposite.

00:30:11.800 --> 00:30:14.900
Dennett claims, that beliefs and desires

00:30:14.900 --> 00:30:18.040
are real states of
people, the states in fact

00:30:18.040 --> 00:30:20.670
which make it possible for us
to predict what they will do

00:30:20.670 --> 00:30:23.210
by adopting the intentional strategy.

00:30:23.210 --> 00:30:25.910
Quote, to a first approximation
the intentional strategy

00:30:25.910 --> 00:30:27.240
consists of treating the object

00:30:27.240 --> 00:30:28.740
whose behavior you want to predict,

00:30:28.740 --> 00:30:31.150
as a rational agent
with beliefs and desires

00:30:31.150 --> 00:30:33.030
and other mental states exhibiting what

00:30:33.030 --> 00:30:36.020
Brentano and others call intentionality.

00:30:36.020 --> 00:30:38.660
To do this you must figure
out what beliefs and desires

00:30:38.660 --> 00:30:39.860
the agent ought to have

00:30:39.860 --> 00:30:42.170
given its place in the
world and its purposes.

00:30:42.170 --> 00:30:44.610
Then you figure out what
desires it ought to have

00:30:44.610 --> 00:30:47.000
on the same considerations,
and finally you predict

00:30:47.000 --> 00:30:50.770
what that rational agent
will act to further

00:30:50.770 --> 00:30:54.100
its goals in the light of
its beliefs and desires.

00:30:54.100 --> 00:30:56.470
The agent therefore must
be reasonable in two ways,

00:30:56.470 --> 00:30:59.050
it must first form its beliefs and desires

00:30:59.050 --> 00:31:00.310
in ways that are reasonable

00:31:00.310 --> 00:31:02.810
and second it must perform
the acts that are reasonable

00:31:02.810 --> 00:31:05.030
given those beliefs and desires.

00:31:05.030 --> 00:31:07.190
This is what it is to adopt
the intentional stance

00:31:07.190 --> 00:31:08.130
towards it.

00:31:08.130 --> 00:31:10.960
What it is finally to
have beliefs and desires,

00:31:10.960 --> 00:31:13.990
is to be and I quote,
an intentional system,

00:31:13.990 --> 00:31:16.140
a system whose behavior is reliably

00:31:16.140 --> 00:31:20.370
and voluminously predictable
via the intentional strategy.

00:31:20.370 --> 00:31:21.523
Now here's a question,

00:31:22.690 --> 00:31:24.750
does it matter why the agent's behavior

00:31:24.750 --> 00:31:26.100
is predictable in this way?

00:31:27.240 --> 00:31:30.360
If I have beliefs and
desires and I'm rational,

00:31:30.360 --> 00:31:32.120
the reason the intentional strategy

00:31:32.120 --> 00:31:34.510
of treating me as a
rational agent works is,

00:31:34.510 --> 00:31:37.870
well, that I am a rational
agent with beliefs and desires.

00:31:37.870 --> 00:31:40.883
It works because it
treats me as what I am.

00:31:40.883 --> 00:31:43.510
If the intentional strategy
works with something

00:31:43.510 --> 00:31:45.840
that doesn't have both beliefs and desires

00:31:45.840 --> 00:31:48.480
and behave rationally on the one hand,

00:31:48.480 --> 00:31:52.754
the success of those reliable
and voluminous predictions

00:31:52.754 --> 00:31:55.483
might seem to be just a mystery.

00:31:56.359 --> 00:32:00.080
But then it serves up an
example that's supposed to show

00:32:00.080 --> 00:32:02.370
why the success of the intentional stance

00:32:02.370 --> 00:32:06.160
can in fact, be quite unmysterious.

00:32:06.160 --> 00:32:08.681
Consider, he suggests,
a computer chess program

00:32:08.681 --> 00:32:11.830
and ask yourself how to
predict what it will do.

00:32:11.830 --> 00:32:14.090
Reading the program or worse,

00:32:14.090 --> 00:32:16.000
looking at the transistors of the computer

00:32:16.000 --> 00:32:19.460
that is implementing, it
isn't going to be much help.

00:32:19.460 --> 00:32:21.030
It would take you too long

00:32:21.030 --> 00:32:23.450
to read and understand the program,

00:32:23.450 --> 00:32:24.730
at least if it's any good.

00:32:24.730 --> 00:32:29.200
A much better way to predict
what moves it will make,

00:32:29.200 --> 00:32:31.430
is to ask yourself this question,

00:32:31.430 --> 00:32:32.850
what would a reasonable person

00:32:32.850 --> 00:32:35.210
who knows the rules and
the aim of chess do,

00:32:35.210 --> 00:32:37.280
faced with this board?

00:32:37.280 --> 00:32:40.600
You'd figure the computer
knows how to play chess,

00:32:40.600 --> 00:32:43.670
wants to win and will act accordingly.

00:32:43.670 --> 00:32:46.940
You would in short, adopt
the intentional stance.

00:32:46.940 --> 00:32:49.380
You would do pretty much
exactly what you would do

00:32:49.380 --> 00:32:51.080
if you were trying to predict the moves

00:32:51.080 --> 00:32:52.892
that a person would make.

00:32:52.892 --> 00:32:55.490
The reason this will
usually work of course,

00:32:55.490 --> 00:32:58.480
is that this is what the
computer was designed to do.

00:32:58.480 --> 00:33:01.226
It is meant to make the
best move that it can.

00:33:01.226 --> 00:33:04.163
The better the design,
the more likely it is

00:33:04.163 --> 00:33:06.570
that the intentional strategy will work

00:33:06.570 --> 00:33:10.540
though and again of course,
if it's really well designed,

00:33:10.540 --> 00:33:13.390
it will see more possibilities
and opportunities

00:33:13.390 --> 00:33:15.710
than most of us mortals and so we will get

00:33:15.710 --> 00:33:16.700
our predictions wrong.

00:33:16.700 --> 00:33:19.010
We may understand looking
backwards why it did what it did

00:33:19.010 --> 00:33:19.987
but we won't be able to predict it,

00:33:19.987 --> 00:33:22.133
'cause it's better at chess than we are.

00:33:23.040 --> 00:33:25.070
Predicting the moves of deep-blue,

00:33:25.070 --> 00:33:29.320
the program that beat Garry
Kasparov in 1997, is something

00:33:29.320 --> 00:33:32.183
only possible for the
grandest of grand masters.

00:33:33.131 --> 00:33:36.150
The Scarecrow it's
around knows, knows how,

00:33:36.150 --> 00:33:38.590
wants and sees in some
of Dennett's writings

00:33:38.590 --> 00:33:41.010
about this topic draw,
attention to the fact,

00:33:41.010 --> 00:33:43.550
that most of us, in adopting
the intentional stance

00:33:43.550 --> 00:33:45.800
towards a computer, and let's admit it,

00:33:45.800 --> 00:33:47.533
we all do that often,

00:33:49.560 --> 00:33:51.930
we nevertheless take talks
of beliefs and desires

00:33:51.930 --> 00:33:54.400
to be figurative, not literal.

00:33:54.400 --> 00:33:56.700
A facon de parler where we are clear

00:33:56.700 --> 00:33:59.460
that our mode is a kind of fiction.

00:33:59.460 --> 00:34:02.960
With humans on the other
hand, we take it literally

00:34:02.960 --> 00:34:05.050
and also with many other animals.

00:34:05.050 --> 00:34:06.880
I think the sheep on our farm

00:34:06.880 --> 00:34:08.910
know that we'll feed them.

00:34:08.910 --> 00:34:10.929
They don't just know it

00:34:10.929 --> 00:34:14.283
and you probably have analogous
thoughts about your dog.

00:34:15.620 --> 00:34:18.490
Dennett tells us that we
should simply postpone

00:34:18.490 --> 00:34:21.810
the question of whether
it really has a mind.

00:34:21.810 --> 00:34:23.840
Unfortunately, there are reasons to worry

00:34:23.840 --> 00:34:25.680
about whether any actual thing

00:34:25.680 --> 00:34:29.590
really has a mind on
Dennett's view, here's why.

00:34:29.590 --> 00:34:32.700
You and I are supposed to
be intentional systems.

00:34:32.700 --> 00:34:35.320
We can be reliably
predicted by approaching us

00:34:35.320 --> 00:34:36.900
with the intentional stance.

00:34:36.900 --> 00:34:39.421
So we meet one of Dennett's criteria.

00:34:39.421 --> 00:34:42.890
But neither you nor I is fully rational.

00:34:42.890 --> 00:34:45.960
Indeed, that we are going
to do irrational things

00:34:45.960 --> 00:34:49.040
is equally voluminously predictable.

00:34:49.040 --> 00:34:50.700
So it remains a bit of a mystery

00:34:50.700 --> 00:34:53.410
why the intentional
strategy succeeds with us

00:34:53.410 --> 00:34:55.223
on the occasions where it does.

00:34:56.170 --> 00:34:59.185
Dennett does not I think,
stress sufficiently the fact,

00:34:59.185 --> 00:35:03.680
that the strategy also fails a great deal.

00:35:03.680 --> 00:35:06.810
This is in part because the
sort of rationality in question

00:35:06.810 --> 00:35:08.530
is extremely demanding.

00:35:08.530 --> 00:35:11.010
It involves having all the
beliefs and desires we ought

00:35:11.010 --> 00:35:13.960
to have and acting only as
we ought to act given them.

00:35:13.960 --> 00:35:16.340
And the evident fact that
many people don't believe

00:35:16.340 --> 00:35:19.800
what they ought to, that the
president was born in Hawaii,

00:35:19.800 --> 00:35:23.290
for example or desire what they should,

00:35:23.290 --> 00:35:25.620
to abstain from smoking for example,

00:35:25.620 --> 00:35:29.580
is one reason why the strategy
is not guaranteed to succeed.

00:35:29.580 --> 00:35:32.200
So, if you have to be fully rational

00:35:32.200 --> 00:35:33.680
to have beliefs and desires,

00:35:33.680 --> 00:35:37.101
then so it seems to me I
don't have beliefs and desires

00:35:37.101 --> 00:35:41.363
and not to put too fine a
point upon it, nor do you.

00:35:42.560 --> 00:35:44.630
Dennett has an answer to the question

00:35:44.630 --> 00:35:49.270
why the intentional strategy
works as often as it does.

00:35:49.270 --> 00:35:52.840
He thinks we were designed
by evolution to work this way

00:35:52.840 --> 00:35:56.830
and so as you see, unlike
many realist philosophers,

00:35:56.830 --> 00:35:59.086
he thinks there is nothing
wrong in speaking of organisms

00:35:59.086 --> 00:36:03.170
or their parts as designed
by evolution to do things.

00:36:03.170 --> 00:36:05.710
This makes sense to him
because as I said he thinks

00:36:05.710 --> 00:36:08.050
that just as we can adopt
the intentional strategy

00:36:08.050 --> 00:36:10.470
towards people and animals and computers,

00:36:10.470 --> 00:36:11.803
we can adopt the design stance

00:36:11.803 --> 00:36:14.730
towards organisms and
the things they produce.

00:36:14.730 --> 00:36:16.660
We can treat them as if they were designed

00:36:16.660 --> 00:36:18.050
to perform certain functions

00:36:18.050 --> 00:36:20.041
and this can allow us to predict again,

00:36:20.041 --> 00:36:23.850
reliably and voluminously,
what they will do.

00:36:23.850 --> 00:36:27.703
Once you know what an alarm
clock or a chainsaw is for,

00:36:28.800 --> 00:36:30.683
you know what it can do.

00:36:30.683 --> 00:36:33.730
So too, for a kidney or a heart.

00:36:33.730 --> 00:36:36.760
Here again, Dennett doesn't
think it helpful to distinguish

00:36:36.760 --> 00:36:38.600
between what was really designed

00:36:38.600 --> 00:36:41.570
by a capital D designer as it were

00:36:41.570 --> 00:36:43.520
and what is merely predictable,

00:36:43.520 --> 00:36:45.653
once we adopt the design stance.

00:36:47.096 --> 00:36:48.920
In the history philosophy many things

00:36:48.920 --> 00:36:50.590
have been called pragmatism,

00:36:50.590 --> 00:36:53.370
but one central candidate
for the name is the thought

00:36:53.370 --> 00:36:55.050
that our theories are to be evaluated

00:36:55.050 --> 00:36:57.240
by what they enable us to do.

00:36:57.240 --> 00:36:59.500
So you might think that
Dennett is here operating

00:36:59.500 --> 00:37:02.690
in this good American
philosophical tradition.

00:37:02.690 --> 00:37:04.510
If the intentional stance enables us

00:37:04.510 --> 00:37:06.410
to predict the behavior of a computer,

00:37:06.410 --> 00:37:08.600
why not just accept that it has beliefs

00:37:08.600 --> 00:37:10.207
and desires and reasons?

00:37:10.207 --> 00:37:12.393
But that is not what he actually says.

00:37:13.290 --> 00:37:16.340
What he proposes instead
is that in the cases

00:37:16.340 --> 00:37:19.223
where the intentional stance
is a rewarding strategy,

00:37:19.223 --> 00:37:21.880
yielding a budget of useful predictions,

00:37:21.880 --> 00:37:24.847
allowing us to manipulate
the world to our advantage,

00:37:24.847 --> 00:37:27.000
shades there of Viahinger,

00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:29.858
we should say, not that
the thing has beliefs,

00:37:29.858 --> 00:37:33.253
but that it sorta has beliefs.

00:37:34.920 --> 00:37:36.960
Dennett's use of the cosy word sorta,

00:37:36.960 --> 00:37:39.940
he pokes fun at the style
of analytic philosophy

00:37:39.940 --> 00:37:42.933
by insisting on calling
it the sorta operator,

00:37:43.960 --> 00:37:45.680
is one of the more interesting things

00:37:45.680 --> 00:37:48.400
in his recent philosophical writings.

00:37:48.400 --> 00:37:52.610
Dennett uses this operator
in two crucial ways;

00:37:52.610 --> 00:37:56.616
first, to talk about anything
to which we can productively

00:37:56.616 --> 00:37:59.100
apply the intentional stance.

00:37:59.100 --> 00:38:01.470
If the strategy works,
then the thing sorta

00:38:01.470 --> 00:38:03.300
believes or desires.

00:38:03.300 --> 00:38:05.780
Second, in the context of evolution

00:38:05.780 --> 00:38:07.290
to talk about the relationship,

00:38:07.290 --> 00:38:09.950
between species and their ancestors.

00:38:09.950 --> 00:38:11.970
Before there were bacteria, he writes,

00:38:11.970 --> 00:38:13.570
there were sorta bacteria,

00:38:13.570 --> 00:38:15.860
and before there were mammals
there were sorta mammals,

00:38:15.860 --> 00:38:19.713
and before there were dogs,
there were sorta dogs and so on.

00:38:21.480 --> 00:38:23.230
It is easy to see one way in which

00:38:23.230 --> 00:38:25.460
these two uses are connected.

00:38:25.460 --> 00:38:27.432
For among the things that sorta believed,

00:38:27.432 --> 00:38:31.486
were some of our sorta ancestors.

00:38:31.486 --> 00:38:33.580
(scoffs) Beliefs came into being gradually

00:38:33.580 --> 00:38:35.360
through an evolutionary process

00:38:35.360 --> 00:38:37.540
and there's no exact moment when suddenly,

00:38:37.540 --> 00:38:40.380
hey presto, full-fledged belief appeared,

00:38:40.380 --> 00:38:42.190
just as there's no exact moment

00:38:42.190 --> 00:38:44.170
when the first mammal was born.

00:38:44.170 --> 00:38:46.560
There is no principle line Dennett writes,

00:38:46.560 --> 00:38:49.640
above which true
comprehension is to be found.

00:38:49.640 --> 00:38:51.160
Now as I say, like many of his ideas

00:38:51.160 --> 00:38:53.300
I think this one is extremely interesting.

00:38:53.300 --> 00:38:56.000
But is also I think, and also typically,

00:38:56.000 --> 00:38:57.500
a little mysterious.

00:38:57.500 --> 00:38:59.240
And the mystery just is the mystery

00:38:59.240 --> 00:39:01.870
of why idealization is
a good strategy here,

00:39:01.870 --> 00:39:04.130
why it so often works.

00:39:04.130 --> 00:39:07.066
So I want to try and unpack
this mystery a little further.

00:39:07.066 --> 00:39:11.020
In particular, let's no
longer postpone the question

00:39:11.020 --> 00:39:14.003
whether anything has any actual beliefs.

00:39:16.040 --> 00:39:17.590
Adopting the intentional stance

00:39:17.590 --> 00:39:19.810
involves applying a
rather elaborate theory

00:39:19.810 --> 00:39:22.030
to predict something's behavior.

00:39:22.030 --> 00:39:25.070
You treat the putative agent
as having beliefs and desires

00:39:25.070 --> 00:39:27.430
ascribed to it by supposing
it believes and desires

00:39:27.430 --> 00:39:29.820
what is reasonable for it
to believe and to desire.

00:39:29.820 --> 00:39:31.390
And then you predict that it will do

00:39:31.390 --> 00:39:32.590
what it would be reasonable to do

00:39:32.590 --> 00:39:35.450
granted that it has those internal states.

00:39:35.450 --> 00:39:38.600
A creature that always had
the rationally required states

00:39:38.600 --> 00:39:40.110
and did the rationally required thing,

00:39:40.110 --> 00:39:42.840
let's call it a cognitive angel,

00:39:42.840 --> 00:39:47.013
would always respond as the
intentional stance requires.

00:39:48.140 --> 00:39:51.450
Its states would be full
fledged beliefs and desires,

00:39:51.450 --> 00:39:54.068
no sorta about it.

00:39:54.068 --> 00:39:56.745
But there are no cognitive angels.

00:39:56.745 --> 00:40:00.030
So in the actual world,
every belief is a belief,

00:40:00.030 --> 00:40:03.690
a sorta belief, and every
desire is a sorta desire.

00:40:03.690 --> 00:40:06.060
No doubt some creatures
in our actual world

00:40:06.060 --> 00:40:08.380
are closer to cognitive angels than others

00:40:08.380 --> 00:40:10.280
in the sense that they will more often do,

00:40:10.280 --> 00:40:12.344
in the circumstances of the actual world,

00:40:12.344 --> 00:40:15.340
what a cognitive angel would have done.

00:40:15.340 --> 00:40:18.980
You and I are no doubt
closer to a cognitive angel

00:40:18.980 --> 00:40:21.803
than your dog, well at least you are.

00:40:23.320 --> 00:40:27.470
Your dog is presumably closer than an ant.

00:40:27.470 --> 00:40:31.030
An ant does a better
cognitive job than an amoeba,

00:40:31.030 --> 00:40:33.240
maybe an amoeba does such a terrible job

00:40:33.240 --> 00:40:35.310
that the intentional strategy with it

00:40:35.310 --> 00:40:36.793
is a complete waste of time.

00:40:37.940 --> 00:40:40.210
In some, the strategy of prediction,

00:40:40.210 --> 00:40:41.780
the strategy we use to make sense

00:40:41.780 --> 00:40:42.990
of the behavior of all the things

00:40:42.990 --> 00:40:45.230
we can usefully treat
as intentional systems,

00:40:45.230 --> 00:40:46.910
is to apply an idealized model,

00:40:46.910 --> 00:40:48.840
knowing that just because it is idealized

00:40:48.840 --> 00:40:51.040
it won't always get things right.

00:40:51.040 --> 00:40:52.803
To say that something
sort of believes is to say

00:40:52.803 --> 00:40:54.960
that the idealized model works for it

00:40:54.960 --> 00:40:56.585
well enough to be getting along with.

00:40:56.585 --> 00:41:00.230
If it worked perfectly, it
would be just plain true

00:41:00.230 --> 00:41:03.767
that we believe, if it works
badly enough it's plain false,

00:41:03.767 --> 00:41:07.120
in between is the vaguely delineated world

00:41:07.120 --> 00:41:08.343
of the sorta true.

00:41:09.610 --> 00:41:12.050
I doubt that Dennett
would accept this picture

00:41:12.050 --> 00:41:16.210
of his proposal, as Robert's
Rules of Order rightly insist,

00:41:16.210 --> 00:41:18.560
there is no such thing
as a friendly amendment.

00:41:19.440 --> 00:41:21.723
Still, looking it this
way, helps us to see,

00:41:21.723 --> 00:41:23.680
that the right answer to the question

00:41:23.680 --> 00:41:27.773
whether anything at all
has a mind might be, sorta.

00:41:28.908 --> 00:41:32.960
But being sorta true is not
a lesser way of being true,

00:41:32.960 --> 00:41:35.683
it is a special way of being false.

00:41:36.650 --> 00:41:39.280
And though it's easy
to see why a true story

00:41:39.280 --> 00:41:41.530
might make the right predictions,

00:41:41.530 --> 00:41:44.250
again, why should a false one?

00:41:44.250 --> 00:41:45.950
And so we're brought back to the question

00:41:45.950 --> 00:41:48.780
whether the fact that we
approximate a rational creature

00:41:48.780 --> 00:41:50.313
isn't something of a mystery.

00:41:51.170 --> 00:41:53.840
Dennett thinks it isn't because
he thinks we can understand

00:41:53.840 --> 00:41:54.964
through evolutionary theory,

00:41:54.964 --> 00:41:57.810
how they came to be creatures like us.

00:41:57.810 --> 00:41:59.150
And at the heart of this understanding

00:41:59.150 --> 00:42:01.180
is a claim he first made a long time ago,

00:42:01.180 --> 00:42:03.410
at least as far back as Elbow Room,

00:42:03.410 --> 00:42:05.470
his book on freedom of the will.

00:42:05.470 --> 00:42:07.040
The world he thinks, is full of quote,

00:42:07.040 --> 00:42:08.880
free-floating rationales,

00:42:08.880 --> 00:42:10.830
reasons why creatures do what they do,

00:42:10.830 --> 00:42:13.820
even though they don't know
that that is why they do them.

00:42:13.820 --> 00:42:16.240
Squirrels burry nuts,

00:42:16.240 --> 00:42:18.491
which they will be able
to eat in the winter.

00:42:18.491 --> 00:42:20.997
They don't know this when they bury them

00:42:20.997 --> 00:42:24.260
but still, that's the
reason why they do it.

00:42:24.260 --> 00:42:26.350
They have purposes as he says,

00:42:26.350 --> 00:42:28.170
but they don't need to know them,

00:42:28.170 --> 00:42:31.440
the need to know principal
rains in the biosphere

00:42:31.440 --> 00:42:33.880
and naturally sexual action itself,

00:42:33.880 --> 00:42:36.517
doesn't need to know what it's doing.

00:42:36.517 --> 00:42:39.820
Dennett thinks that the
evolution has endowed us

00:42:39.820 --> 00:42:43.300
on the other hand, with the
capacity not just to have

00:42:43.300 --> 00:42:45.980
but also to know our purposes.

00:42:45.980 --> 00:42:47.830
And a proper evolutionary account

00:42:47.830 --> 00:42:50.430
of how we came to be sorta agents,

00:42:50.430 --> 00:42:53.910
with sorta beliefs and sort of
desires and sorta intentions

00:42:53.910 --> 00:42:55.700
will make it less mysterious he thinks,

00:42:55.700 --> 00:42:58.900
that we respond to reasons demands.

00:42:58.900 --> 00:43:00.360
But notice that the explanation here

00:43:00.360 --> 00:43:04.830
of why the intentional strategy
works for us in essence is,

00:43:04.830 --> 00:43:06.970
that the design stance shows us

00:43:06.970 --> 00:43:09.741
why we have come to be
intentional systems.

00:43:09.741 --> 00:43:11.618
And what does that mean?

00:43:11.618 --> 00:43:14.480
Well, that it is as if we were designed

00:43:14.480 --> 00:43:16.740
to have intentional states.

00:43:16.740 --> 00:43:19.170
But the mystery of why we can be managed

00:43:19.170 --> 00:43:21.210
by an intentional systems approach,

00:43:21.210 --> 00:43:24.130
is not explained by
saying that it is as if

00:43:24.130 --> 00:43:26.340
we were designed to work intentionally,

00:43:26.340 --> 00:43:28.170
it would only be explained if we were

00:43:28.170 --> 00:43:30.290
designed to work intentionally.

00:43:30.290 --> 00:43:33.403
We have just replaced
one mystery with another.

00:43:34.570 --> 00:43:36.560
It is impasses such as
these that lead people

00:43:36.560 --> 00:43:38.140
to want to say that
the fact that we can be

00:43:38.140 --> 00:43:39.860
predicted and controlled in these ways,

00:43:39.860 --> 00:43:41.770
shows that there is an underlying truth

00:43:41.770 --> 00:43:42.640
that the theory captures.

00:43:42.640 --> 00:43:44.740
That's why Dennett in some mood says

00:43:44.740 --> 00:43:46.780
we do have beliefs and desires.

00:43:46.780 --> 00:43:49.140
Ian Hacking has suggested
that what gives us reason

00:43:49.140 --> 00:43:51.231
to be a realist about
things like positrons

00:43:51.231 --> 00:43:53.900
is that we can manipulate
them, intervening in the world

00:43:53.900 --> 00:43:55.802
on the basis of our beliefs about them.

00:43:55.802 --> 00:43:58.040
Once he tells us when he was discussing

00:43:58.040 --> 00:43:59.700
a physics experiment with a friend,

00:43:59.700 --> 00:44:03.111
he asked how you altered the
charge on a niobium ball.

00:44:03.111 --> 00:44:05.397
"Well, at that stage," said my friend,

00:44:05.397 --> 00:44:08.107
"we spray it with positrons
to increase the charge

00:44:08.107 --> 00:44:10.820
"or with electrons to
decrease the charge."

00:44:10.820 --> 00:44:13.007
Hacking's response, "From that day forth

00:44:13.007 --> 00:44:14.701
"I've been a scientific realist,

00:44:14.701 --> 00:44:17.197
"so far as I'm concerned
if you can spray them,

00:44:17.197 --> 00:44:19.550
"they're real." (audience laughs lightly)

00:44:19.550 --> 00:44:21.410
And notice that like Viahinger,

00:44:21.410 --> 00:44:23.700
his thought is not about
saving the phenomena

00:44:23.700 --> 00:44:27.130
but about managing the world,
he's on Viahinger's side here.

00:44:27.130 --> 00:44:30.558
Nancy Cartwright, it seems
odd to mention them both

00:44:30.558 --> 00:44:33.330
regularly without mentioning
that they were once married

00:44:33.330 --> 00:44:34.453
to one another but I won't.

00:44:34.453 --> 00:44:37.373
Nancy Cartwright as I just pointed out,

00:44:37.373 --> 00:44:40.780
thinks that the success of
the strategies of physics

00:44:40.780 --> 00:44:43.360
gives us reason to
believe in the capacities

00:44:43.360 --> 00:44:46.858
our physical laws, atom
break in precisely.

00:44:46.858 --> 00:44:49.629
She has a book called how
the laws of physics lie.

00:44:49.629 --> 00:44:53.820
What better reason we might
ask by parity of reasoning,

00:44:53.820 --> 00:44:55.320
could there be than the successes

00:44:55.320 --> 00:44:56.830
of the intentional strategy,

00:44:56.830 --> 00:44:59.280
for believing in the intentional states?

00:44:59.280 --> 00:45:01.533
Well, here's a better reason,

00:45:03.390 --> 00:45:04.920
we'd have a better reason if the theory

00:45:04.920 --> 00:45:06.900
didn't get so much wrong.

00:45:06.900 --> 00:45:09.730
In particular, if it
didn't treat us as rational

00:45:09.730 --> 00:45:12.150
in ways we already know we're not

00:45:12.150 --> 00:45:14.763
and predict that we will
do things that we don't do.

00:45:17.152 --> 00:45:20.140
On each trip of explanation every,

00:45:20.140 --> 00:45:23.330
I'm sorry on each trip,
every train of explanation

00:45:23.330 --> 00:45:26.320
comes to its last stop.

00:45:26.320 --> 00:45:27.610
Unless you think the whole world

00:45:27.610 --> 00:45:30.180
is the working out of
conceptual necessities,

00:45:30.180 --> 00:45:31.960
you will have to accept that there are

00:45:31.960 --> 00:45:34.440
some brute empirical truths.

00:45:34.440 --> 00:45:35.763
And for the moment I am inclined to think

00:45:35.763 --> 00:45:38.410
that the fact that the
intentional strategy works

00:45:38.410 --> 00:45:43.080
to the extent that it does,
is in that way, brute.

00:45:43.080 --> 00:45:45.510
Evolution apparently equipped us

00:45:45.510 --> 00:45:47.330
with the intentional strategy,

00:45:47.330 --> 00:45:52.210
and it was built-in but,

00:45:52.210 --> 00:45:53.790
it was sorry, it was built into us,

00:45:53.790 --> 00:45:55.390
I seem to have lost a page here,

00:45:56.680 --> 00:45:58.730
presumably because it was adaptive.

00:45:58.730 --> 00:46:01.240
But it seems to me that
it's not at all clear yet

00:46:01.240 --> 00:46:02.600
why it is adaptive.

00:46:02.600 --> 00:46:04.970
What features of it led to its selection.

00:46:04.970 --> 00:46:07.650
And the hypothesis that
we really have states

00:46:07.650 --> 00:46:09.490
that are like beliefs and desires,

00:46:09.490 --> 00:46:11.850
is only one candid explanation.

00:46:11.850 --> 00:46:13.870
Now a par with the churchlands,

00:46:13.870 --> 00:46:16.340
you can't really doubt that you yourself

00:46:16.340 --> 00:46:18.340
have beliefs and desires.

00:46:18.340 --> 00:46:20.110
It's hard realistically to doubt

00:46:20.110 --> 00:46:21.500
that other people have them,

00:46:21.500 --> 00:46:24.530
except in the skeptical
or paranoid frame of mind

00:46:24.530 --> 00:46:26.750
that can have you doubting
that anything at all

00:46:26.750 --> 00:46:28.954
is really as it seems.

00:46:28.954 --> 00:46:33.629
But it could be true,
even if you were wrong,

00:46:33.629 --> 00:46:36.170
(speaks foreign language),
what cannot be doubted,

00:46:36.170 --> 00:46:37.243
need not be true.

00:46:39.000 --> 00:46:41.630
That idealization sorta works then,

00:46:41.630 --> 00:46:44.220
is in many cases just
something that turns out

00:46:44.220 --> 00:46:45.883
to be simply true.

00:46:47.057 --> 00:46:49.530
There is in any case a reason to doubt

00:46:49.530 --> 00:46:52.630
whether the question I
am asking is a fair one.

00:46:52.630 --> 00:46:56.930
You cannot ask seriously why
our idealizations work for us

00:46:56.930 --> 00:46:59.620
except from the point of view
of a picture of the world

00:46:59.620 --> 00:47:02.340
that includes both us
and our idealizations.

00:47:02.340 --> 00:47:05.850
A picture that is in that sense...

00:47:08.940 --> 00:47:13.940
sorry, better than the one that
we actually currently have.

00:47:19.830 --> 00:47:21.670
So that it seems to me that there's just

00:47:21.670 --> 00:47:23.730
a reasonable thing we can say,

00:47:23.730 --> 00:47:25.720
which is that we cannot do anything

00:47:25.720 --> 00:47:28.170
from the point of view of
a theory we don't have.

00:47:29.052 --> 00:47:32.510
If the question is how
to understand the fact

00:47:32.510 --> 00:47:34.020
that our idealizations work,

00:47:34.020 --> 00:47:35.510
we have to understand that question

00:47:35.510 --> 00:47:37.450
against the background of a picture.

00:47:37.450 --> 00:47:38.530
And the picture has to be one

00:47:38.530 --> 00:47:40.267
which includes both us
in our idealizations

00:47:40.267 --> 00:47:41.770
and if it's going to be very interesting

00:47:41.770 --> 00:47:43.330
it had better be a better theory

00:47:43.330 --> 00:47:44.790
than the one we've currently got.

00:47:44.790 --> 00:47:46.680
But we can't do anything
from the point of a theory

00:47:46.680 --> 00:47:47.680
that we haven't got.

00:47:48.670 --> 00:47:51.090
And if that's right,
this sort of idealization

00:47:51.090 --> 00:47:54.113
will only be possible as it
were in the rear view mirror.

00:47:55.060 --> 00:47:59.260
And that should lead us to
revisit Viahinger's explanation

00:47:59.260 --> 00:48:02.650
as to why idealization is necessary.

00:48:02.650 --> 00:48:05.310
The question whether the
complexity for us of the world

00:48:05.310 --> 00:48:08.030
explains our need for idealization,

00:48:08.030 --> 00:48:09.820
requires us to have a picture,

00:48:09.820 --> 00:48:12.880
of our own relation to the world.

00:48:12.880 --> 00:48:15.290
If the only picture we have of the world

00:48:15.290 --> 00:48:18.400
and of ourselves is an idealized one,

00:48:18.400 --> 00:48:21.110
we have no strictly
and totally true theory

00:48:21.110 --> 00:48:23.280
with which to approach this question.

00:48:23.280 --> 00:48:26.950
We can try to answer it with
these useful false theories

00:48:26.950 --> 00:48:29.950
but they will ex hypothesi,
represent the world

00:48:29.950 --> 00:48:31.700
as simpler than it is.

00:48:31.700 --> 00:48:34.510
So once more, it will only
be from the point of view

00:48:34.510 --> 00:48:36.600
of theories that are better than ours,

00:48:36.600 --> 00:48:39.190
that our question can be asked.

00:48:39.190 --> 00:48:42.003
So we can look back to Newtonian physics

00:48:42.003 --> 00:48:44.230
and ask why it worked well enough

00:48:44.230 --> 00:48:45.930
in the circumstances of our world,

00:48:45.930 --> 00:48:49.690
even though it ignored complexities
of which it was unaware.

00:48:49.690 --> 00:48:51.831
And we can see from where we stand now,

00:48:51.831 --> 00:48:53.730
that it would have been very difficult

00:48:53.730 --> 00:48:56.940
with the tools both
experimental and theoretical

00:48:56.940 --> 00:48:58.357
that the Newtonians mobilized,

00:48:58.357 --> 00:49:01.731
to represent these
post-newtonian complexities.

00:49:01.731 --> 00:49:04.190
I'm inclined to think that the question

00:49:04.190 --> 00:49:06.730
I have been trying to
get Dennett to answer,

00:49:06.730 --> 00:49:10.430
only makes sense as a
question we will ask later,

00:49:10.430 --> 00:49:12.910
looking backwards at our present selves.

00:49:12.910 --> 00:49:15.120
And only then, because we will suprose

00:49:15.120 --> 00:49:17.550
that our later theories are better.

00:49:17.550 --> 00:49:20.470
If that is right, then here as elsewhere

00:49:20.470 --> 00:49:22.658
in Hegel's justly famous phrase,

00:49:22.658 --> 00:49:27.420
the owl of Minerva flies at dusk.

00:49:27.420 --> 00:49:28.253
Thank you.

00:49:29.235 --> 00:49:31.485
(applause)

00:49:36.720 --> 00:49:38.590
- [Man] I guess I'd like to ask about

00:49:41.295 --> 00:49:44.150
the idea that common
sense psychology involves

00:49:44.150 --> 00:49:46.370
this idealization of rationality.

00:49:46.370 --> 00:49:49.180
I guess what I wonder is,
isn't it just a mistake

00:49:49.180 --> 00:49:51.596
Dennett makes to say that we actually use

00:49:51.596 --> 00:49:54.430
an idealization of rationality?

00:49:54.430 --> 00:49:58.430
Suppose I own a casino and
I'm tryna set up the casino,

00:49:58.430 --> 00:50:00.170
I wanna make a lot of money from this,

00:50:00.170 --> 00:50:05.170
then idealizing that my patrons
have complete rationality

00:50:06.610 --> 00:50:09.650
is (chuckles) going to make
life very difficult for me.

00:50:09.650 --> 00:50:13.140
What I need, actually is
a very good understanding

00:50:13.140 --> 00:50:15.690
of all the ways in which
they're irrational.

00:50:15.690 --> 00:50:19.640
I mean I could be exhibiting
my grasp of folk psychology,

00:50:19.640 --> 00:50:23.968
I could be the apotheosis of
a skilled folks psychologist

00:50:23.968 --> 00:50:26.569
working with my clients irrationalities,

00:50:26.569 --> 00:50:29.890
I don't need an idealization
of rationality here.

00:50:29.890 --> 00:50:32.670
So it may be true that sometimes we assume

00:50:32.670 --> 00:50:35.990
that people will get
the easy things right,

00:50:35.990 --> 00:50:38.720
but if you're good at
interpersonal relations,

00:50:38.720 --> 00:50:40.510
that may involve you often assuming

00:50:40.510 --> 00:50:42.880
that they're gonna get stuff wrong.

00:50:42.880 --> 00:50:43.713
- Good.

00:50:46.100 --> 00:50:49.472
I mean I agree with what you just said.

00:50:49.472 --> 00:50:53.300
I think that our capacity
to understand other people,

00:50:53.300 --> 00:50:55.783
to predict them, to respond to them,

00:50:57.170 --> 00:51:00.820
depends upon our knowing some truths

00:51:00.820 --> 00:51:04.500
about the ways in which
we characteristically

00:51:04.500 --> 00:51:07.579
deviate from all sorts
of forms of rationality.

00:51:07.579 --> 00:51:09.620
This is a truth that even economists

00:51:09.620 --> 00:51:11.177
have finally discovered (man chuckles).

00:51:18.268 --> 00:51:19.430
I think that that shows that Dennett

00:51:19.430 --> 00:51:21.080
sort of put it in the wrong way,

00:51:21.080 --> 00:51:23.702
I don't think it shows
that he's clearly wrong.

00:51:23.702 --> 00:51:25.880
And this relates to the question

00:51:25.880 --> 00:51:27.540
that I put aside for the book

00:51:27.540 --> 00:51:29.750
about the role of these idealized models

00:51:29.750 --> 00:51:33.003
in understanding things as
opposed to in prediction.

00:51:35.299 --> 00:51:38.830
We would like an account,
well philosophers anyway,

00:51:38.830 --> 00:51:41.303
would like an account of what beliefs are.

00:51:42.282 --> 00:51:46.110
And it seems to me very
hard to give an account

00:51:46.110 --> 00:51:47.960
of what beliefs are in a way that ignores

00:51:47.960 --> 00:51:52.783
certain norms about how beliefs
are supposed to operate.

00:51:53.903 --> 00:51:58.740
So we do have, in our conception
of what the states are

00:51:58.740 --> 00:52:01.100
that we're ascribing to people,

00:52:01.100 --> 00:52:05.120
we have in not just in
philosophy but in ordinary life,

00:52:05.120 --> 00:52:08.940
notions about what as you
said in the obvious case,

00:52:08.940 --> 00:52:13.380
it would be reasonable
for a person to believe,

00:52:13.380 --> 00:52:14.900
what it would be
reasonable for them to do,

00:52:14.900 --> 00:52:17.690
given what we think they
believe in desire and so on.

00:52:17.690 --> 00:52:20.980
Now, we also have again in common sense,

00:52:20.980 --> 00:52:23.460
a bunch of ideas about
things that are obstacles

00:52:23.460 --> 00:52:26.203
to carrying out the required thing.

00:52:31.410 --> 00:52:33.090
We know that there are systemic ways

00:52:33.090 --> 00:52:35.780
in which people make
failures of reasoning,

00:52:35.780 --> 00:52:38.750
we know that for example,
forming beliefs about yourself

00:52:38.750 --> 00:52:40.300
is especially difficult because

00:52:41.670 --> 00:52:43.040
we're designed to have an interest

00:52:43.040 --> 00:52:45.159
in representing ourselves
as better than we are.

00:52:45.159 --> 00:52:48.560
There are lots of things we
know informally about that.

00:52:48.560 --> 00:52:51.110
But it's still the case
that those are explanations

00:52:51.960 --> 00:52:54.750
that attend to beliefs as things which

00:52:54.750 --> 00:52:56.788
in the absence of those things,

00:52:56.788 --> 00:53:00.373
would behave in the way
that reason requires.

00:53:03.280 --> 00:53:04.984
When you're building your casino,

00:53:04.984 --> 00:53:07.783
when you're managing your casino,

00:53:08.810 --> 00:53:13.570
you have to treat people
both as for many purposes,

00:53:13.570 --> 00:53:16.100
as doing what their beliefs
and desires require them to do.

00:53:16.100 --> 00:53:18.070
They want to play the game,

00:53:18.070 --> 00:53:20.290
they'll be willing to give you money,

00:53:20.290 --> 00:53:23.003
in exchange for chips and so on.

00:53:23.986 --> 00:53:26.790
All these things involve
treating them as having

00:53:26.790 --> 00:53:29.500
desires and beliefs that are
working in the correct way

00:53:29.500 --> 00:53:33.300
but then as you say, you will require,

00:53:35.150 --> 00:53:36.640
if your casino is going to make any money,

00:53:36.640 --> 00:53:38.510
you will require them to make bets

00:53:38.510 --> 00:53:40.727
that they ought not to make.

00:53:40.727 --> 00:53:43.450
And you know some things
as a casino operator

00:53:43.450 --> 00:53:45.870
about what will make them do that.

00:53:45.870 --> 00:53:48.840
For example, we know
that however irrational,

00:53:48.840 --> 00:53:50.980
however clearly and false it is,

00:53:50.980 --> 00:53:54.540
people think that they can
be on a winning streak.

00:53:54.540 --> 00:53:57.100
So we should be attentive to
people who've won a few things

00:53:57.100 --> 00:53:58.915
and encourage them to bet more,

00:53:58.915 --> 00:53:59.830
that's one of the things we know.

00:53:59.830 --> 00:54:04.330
Even though a properly scientifically

00:54:04.330 --> 00:54:06.340
