01:06:51.320 --> 01:06:53.160
And one of the things that I think

01:06:53.160 --> 01:06:55.840
reading Viahinger has made
me think about is that

01:06:57.820 --> 01:07:02.150
as I said, useful means
useful for some purpose.

01:07:02.150 --> 01:07:04.520
I think it's often very unclear

01:07:04.520 --> 01:07:06.760
what the purposes are with which we

01:07:06.760 --> 01:07:09.210
mobilize our representations.

01:07:09.210 --> 01:07:11.380
He says controlling the
world, that is one of them,

01:07:11.380 --> 01:07:14.100
but as I said understanding
the world is another

01:07:14.100 --> 01:07:16.850
and that's a great deal less clear

01:07:16.850 --> 01:07:20.150
what the criteria of
success and failure are

01:07:20.150 --> 01:07:21.530
and controlling the world we succeed

01:07:21.530 --> 01:07:24.380
if we sort of get what we wanted.

01:07:24.380 --> 01:07:28.223
Understanding, it's less
clear to me that we have

01:07:28.223 --> 01:07:29.860
sort of this solid picture.

01:07:29.860 --> 01:07:32.210
So I would say that my sort of conclusion

01:07:32.210 --> 01:07:35.600
from all this is that our
understanding of the world

01:07:35.600 --> 01:07:40.490
is held in many incompatible pictures

01:07:40.490 --> 01:07:43.562
and that there's a reason
to hold on to some pictures

01:07:43.562 --> 01:07:46.830
that are known to be wrong

01:07:46.830 --> 01:07:49.450
because the fact that they're wrong,

01:07:49.450 --> 01:07:52.725
doesn't mean that they aren't
useful for some purpose.

01:07:52.725 --> 01:07:55.747
Though it can be unclear
what that purpose is.

01:07:55.747 --> 01:07:56.647
- [Man] Thank you.

01:08:05.380 --> 01:08:06.213
- [Campbell] I would really like

01:08:06.213 --> 01:08:09.063
to ask you one more question
and I hope I may do that.

01:08:10.400 --> 01:08:12.580
I wonder if you really need Dennett

01:08:12.580 --> 01:08:15.437
to frame the puzzle that interests you.

01:08:15.437 --> 01:08:17.160
And there are two things in Dennett,

01:08:17.160 --> 01:08:19.019
One is there's some
kind of instrumentalism.

01:08:19.019 --> 01:08:21.357
There's a familiar pattern

01:08:21.357 --> 01:08:22.940
where there's a lot of instrumentalism

01:08:22.940 --> 01:08:24.040
and then there's a lot of talk about

01:08:24.040 --> 01:08:25.610
how I'm not an instrumentalist.

01:08:25.610 --> 01:08:30.610
But suppose you were as
uncompromising a realist as you like

01:08:31.960 --> 01:08:34.530
about the mental life,
I say consciousness,

01:08:34.530 --> 01:08:37.230
rationality, all that's just there,

01:08:37.230 --> 01:08:40.760
is got nothing to do reliable
and voluminous prediction.

01:08:40.760 --> 01:08:44.180
It's the only bit of the
universe that really matters,

01:08:44.180 --> 01:08:46.580
that's what's important
to us the mental life.

01:08:46.580 --> 01:08:48.010
Everything else only matters

01:08:48.010 --> 01:08:50.100
because of its connection
to the mental life

01:08:50.100 --> 01:08:51.770
and that's not to be explained

01:08:51.770 --> 01:08:53.660
as instrumental for something else,

01:08:53.660 --> 01:08:56.563
that's just there a bit
of reality to be studied.

01:08:57.701 --> 01:09:00.100
Now even if you have such a view,

01:09:00.100 --> 01:09:02.272
which I take it is opposite to Dennett's

01:09:02.272 --> 01:09:05.271
your puzzle it seems to
me you could still raise

01:09:05.271 --> 01:09:07.600
because it would still be true,

01:09:07.600 --> 01:09:09.147
it would be as true as it ever was

01:09:09.147 --> 01:09:14.147
that we are using rationality
as an idealization

01:09:14.590 --> 01:09:17.140
in understanding this bit of the world

01:09:17.140 --> 01:09:19.274
and your question will still be live.

01:09:19.274 --> 01:09:20.930
How does that work?

01:09:20.930 --> 01:09:24.284
How can it be helpful to
understand this bit of reality

01:09:24.284 --> 01:09:27.925
when we just know that we're not rational.

01:09:27.925 --> 01:09:31.744
So the as if comes in twice here.

01:09:31.744 --> 01:09:35.790
As if comes in in your picture of what

01:09:35.790 --> 01:09:36.920
the psychological life is.

01:09:36.920 --> 01:09:39.720
I mean one way of putting
down its pictures to say,

01:09:39.720 --> 01:09:41.140
you don't really have a mind,

01:09:41.140 --> 01:09:42.930
it's only as if you have a mind

01:09:42.930 --> 01:09:44.810
and we can use that to predict.

01:09:44.810 --> 01:09:46.430
You don't need that bit.

01:09:46.430 --> 01:09:49.731
You want, we've got a
mind, whatever that is

01:09:49.731 --> 01:09:53.720
and we use this ideal and
we use this idealization of

01:09:53.720 --> 01:09:56.730
as if we were rational
and that's the key thing.

01:09:56.730 --> 01:09:58.460
Is that right?

01:09:58.460 --> 01:10:01.690
- I think, yes the problem
would still arise on that view.

01:10:01.690 --> 01:10:05.887
I'm a little bit interested
in Dennett's way of doing it

01:10:07.330 --> 01:10:12.330
because I'm old enough to have grown up

01:10:12.480 --> 01:10:15.640
thinking there was an interesting
problem about the minds.

01:10:15.640 --> 01:10:16.473
- [Campbell] Oh we do.
(giggling)

01:10:16.473 --> 01:10:17.921
- Lots of people nowadays seem to think

01:10:17.921 --> 01:10:18.754
that there is--

01:10:18.754 --> 01:10:21.254
(both mumble)

01:10:24.370 --> 01:10:25.750
And so I'm interested in as it were

01:10:25.750 --> 01:10:29.300
the reasons why we might
think that other creatures

01:10:29.300 --> 01:10:33.207
including ourselves, have
minds, I mean each other.

01:10:33.207 --> 01:10:36.110
I agree that the reasons
why I think I have a mind

01:10:36.110 --> 01:10:39.040
might be peculiar and distinctive

01:10:39.040 --> 01:10:43.313
but I'm and you know return
is obviously for you.

01:10:46.332 --> 01:10:49.169
But I guess I am interested in

01:10:49.169 --> 01:10:52.520
whether we can say how it is

01:10:52.520 --> 01:10:55.090
that it's possible given the fact

01:10:55.090 --> 01:10:56.980
that the way I know what I think

01:10:56.980 --> 01:11:00.030
is so different from the way
that you know what you think,

01:11:00.030 --> 01:11:02.280
that I can know what you think.

01:11:02.280 --> 01:11:04.540
And this whole tradition

01:11:06.580 --> 01:11:09.120
which includes Viahinger and Dennett

01:11:09.120 --> 01:11:10.890
is sort of broadly empiricists

01:11:10.890 --> 01:11:13.570
in its attempt to understand the mind

01:11:13.570 --> 01:11:17.400
as not one's own mind,
but the minds of others

01:11:17.400 --> 01:11:19.890
including other organisms and humans.

01:11:19.890 --> 01:11:22.070
I think in a way...

01:11:23.210 --> 01:11:24.043
Look...

01:11:26.540 --> 01:11:29.250
there's no practical doubt in my mind

01:11:29.250 --> 01:11:33.010
about whether other people have minds,

01:11:33.010 --> 01:11:34.937
particular other people have minds.

01:11:34.937 --> 01:11:38.270
Some people sometimes have a
kind of moment when they...

01:11:38.270 --> 01:11:40.940
I don't have that experience.

01:11:40.940 --> 01:11:45.020
But I do have that thought
about some other animals,

01:11:45.020 --> 01:11:46.563
as I mentioned sheep.

01:11:48.350 --> 01:11:49.790
I'm interested in the question,

01:11:49.790 --> 01:11:53.140
how sensible it is to think of them,

01:11:53.140 --> 01:11:55.463
it seems to be obvious
that they have perceptions.

01:11:57.470 --> 01:12:00.150
That's not one of the
things I'm not clear about.

01:12:00.150 --> 01:12:02.009
But I am unclear about how much

01:12:02.009 --> 01:12:04.350
one should say about them in terms of

01:12:04.350 --> 01:12:08.050
the language of belief, desire,

01:12:08.050 --> 01:12:11.000
I don't find myself tempted to
think that they hope things.

01:12:14.000 --> 01:12:16.410
I think they have intentions
at least sometimes,

01:12:16.410 --> 01:12:17.530
but I'm not sure.

01:12:17.530 --> 01:12:21.370
And in trying to decide
what that worry amounts to,

01:12:21.370 --> 01:12:23.540
I think the sort of thing
that Dennett is doing

01:12:23.540 --> 01:12:24.975
with the intentional sense

01:12:24.975 --> 01:12:27.030
is one of the kinds of answers.

01:12:27.030 --> 01:12:29.590
But I agree that for you and me,

01:12:29.590 --> 01:12:30.960
the question whether...

01:12:32.090 --> 01:12:34.330
I don't understand the Churchland view

01:12:34.330 --> 01:12:36.077
that it might turn out--

01:12:36.077 --> 01:12:38.266
- [Campbell] Yeah.

01:12:38.266 --> 01:12:39.687
- It's not that their view
that we could turn out

01:12:39.687 --> 01:12:40.520
that we don't have minds,

01:12:40.520 --> 01:12:41.353
it's their view that we could turn out

01:12:41.353 --> 01:12:43.617
to have minds that were
sort of radically different

01:12:43.617 --> 01:12:46.663
from the way they appear to us to be.

01:12:51.908 --> 01:12:54.970
I'm really interested in the
sort of thing Charlie works on

01:12:54.970 --> 01:12:58.280
which is the relationship
between that story

01:12:58.280 --> 01:13:00.225
and the neurobiological story.

01:13:00.225 --> 01:13:01.570
It's not that I don't think
that's an interesting question,

01:13:01.570 --> 01:13:03.040
but I don't think of the
neurobiological story

01:13:03.040 --> 01:13:08.040
as one that could force me
to abandon this other story.

01:13:09.318 --> 01:13:12.860
And I'm in part saying that
because of the general view

01:13:12.860 --> 01:13:14.750
that I just suggested, which is that

01:13:14.750 --> 01:13:19.610
we need lots of stories that
are doing different jobs for us

01:13:19.610 --> 01:13:23.990
and I suppose I'm arguing that actually,

01:13:23.990 --> 01:13:28.990
against claims for the importance
of the unity of knowledge,

01:13:29.100 --> 01:13:32.890
I'm arguing that our
knowledge is held in many,

01:13:32.890 --> 01:13:36.209
incompatible systems of representation

01:13:36.209 --> 01:13:40.726
and if we were God, maybe
we could integrate them all.

01:13:40.726 --> 01:13:42.900
If we were cognitive angels
we could integrate them

01:13:42.900 --> 01:13:43.733
although we're not.

01:13:43.733 --> 01:13:47.290
And we never will be, so
we're always going to need

01:13:47.290 --> 01:13:48.410
lots of different pictures.

01:13:48.410 --> 01:13:50.580
And one of the pictures
that I just don't see how

01:13:50.580 --> 01:13:54.251
it would make sense for a human
being to try to be without

01:13:54.251 --> 01:13:55.701
is this picture of ourselves

01:13:55.701 --> 01:13:57.880
as wanting things and hoping
for things and desiring things

01:13:57.880 --> 01:14:01.030
and thinking things and having reasons

01:14:01.030 --> 01:14:04.050
for doing and thinking and feeling things.

01:14:04.050 --> 01:14:05.103
That seems to me,

01:14:07.190 --> 01:14:10.490
I just don't know how I could do without.

01:14:12.406 --> 01:14:14.406
How we could do without.

01:14:15.417 --> 01:14:17.140
- [Campbell] Please come up.

01:14:21.530 --> 01:14:22.820
- [Lady] So I'm gonna
go back to two things

01:14:22.820 --> 01:14:24.440
that you've said about make-believe

01:14:24.440 --> 01:14:27.060
and also about the final image

01:14:27.060 --> 01:14:29.354
about going off into the future.

01:14:29.354 --> 01:14:31.380
From an empirical perspective,

01:14:31.380 --> 01:14:32.860
at least one account you might have

01:14:32.860 --> 01:14:35.224
about why kids are making believe,

01:14:35.224 --> 01:14:38.790
is that one of the
capacities we need to have

01:14:38.790 --> 01:14:40.740
to make cognitive progress,

01:14:40.740 --> 01:14:43.622
is the capacity to say here's
the belief that I hold now,

01:14:43.622 --> 01:14:47.530
here's how it fits the data,
here's an alternative belief

01:14:47.530 --> 01:14:49.190
which I currently do not hold,

01:14:49.190 --> 01:14:52.620
which I currently don't think it's true,

01:14:52.620 --> 01:14:54.930
I wanna check how that fits the data.

01:14:54.930 --> 01:14:59.010
So I have some new set of
data, I've done an experiment

01:14:59.010 --> 01:15:02.560
a.k.a. gotten into
everything in my nursery

01:15:02.560 --> 01:15:04.755
and now I have a new bunch of data,

01:15:04.755 --> 01:15:06.415
I have a current belief,

01:15:06.415 --> 01:15:08.650
I check that belief against the data,

01:15:08.650 --> 01:15:10.060
but here's an alternative belief

01:15:10.060 --> 01:15:11.550
that I'm gonna check against the data.

01:15:11.550 --> 01:15:14.860
and if you don't actually
have the cognitive capacity

01:15:14.860 --> 01:15:19.830
to say here's an alternative
belief, it's false as of now.

01:15:19.830 --> 01:15:23.900
But if it were true, here's
what the consequences would be,

01:15:23.900 --> 01:15:24.733
here's the data.

01:15:24.733 --> 01:15:28.120
how does that actually fit
with the potential consequences

01:15:28.120 --> 01:15:30.307
and the capacity to
sometimes override and say,

01:15:30.307 --> 01:15:31.140
"Oh, look at that!

01:15:31.140 --> 01:15:32.393
"The thing that I thought before was false

01:15:32.393 --> 01:15:33.940
"and this thing is true."

01:15:33.940 --> 01:15:35.450
Then you wouldn't be able to make

01:15:35.450 --> 01:15:37.510
the kind of cognitive progress
that we actually make.

01:15:37.510 --> 01:15:39.650
And from that perspective
what you're doing

01:15:39.650 --> 01:15:41.274
when you're making believe is essentially

01:15:41.274 --> 01:15:44.037
exercising this capacity to say,

01:15:44.037 --> 01:15:46.717
"Here's a premise, it's important

01:15:46.717 --> 01:15:48.277
"that I currently think that it's false

01:15:48.277 --> 01:15:51.897
"because I don't want to get
confused about my predictions,

01:15:51.897 --> 01:15:54.197
"but I can think if it were true,

01:15:54.197 --> 01:15:55.077
"that if this were true,

01:15:55.077 --> 01:15:57.000
"then here's what the
consequences would be."

01:15:57.000 --> 01:15:58.838
So I think there's a relationship between

01:15:58.838 --> 01:16:00.369
and I think part of the reason why

01:16:00.369 --> 01:16:02.471
it seems plausible to have idealizations

01:16:02.471 --> 01:16:06.410
is because we and as a matter
of fact also four-year-olds

01:16:06.410 --> 01:16:10.160
know that the current
belief might be susceptible

01:16:10.160 --> 01:16:13.390
to this kind of replacement by what,

01:16:13.390 --> 01:16:17.740
at the moment is just the as if, beliefs.

01:16:17.740 --> 01:16:19.910
So I think there's a
connection between those two

01:16:19.910 --> 01:16:23.184
that actually makes sense
out of why it is that

01:16:23.184 --> 01:16:26.220
we would be not only entertain as ifs

01:16:26.220 --> 01:16:28.190
when we're doing things like make believe,

01:16:28.190 --> 01:16:30.535
but the sense in which we could say that

01:16:30.535 --> 01:16:34.590
we know that the belief
that we currently have

01:16:34.590 --> 01:16:35.990
is gonna turn out to be false,

01:16:35.990 --> 01:16:38.810
but it's still useful and
important for us to hold it.

01:16:38.810 --> 01:16:41.970
And it's also important for
us to hold the alternative,

01:16:41.970 --> 01:16:44.103
to be able to work with
the alternative hypothesis

01:16:44.103 --> 01:16:45.783
as if it were true.

01:16:45.783 --> 01:16:46.616
- Mhmn.

01:16:50.237 --> 01:16:52.130
I don't know what to say,
except that that seems

01:16:52.130 --> 01:16:54.023
absolutely right to me,

01:16:54.023 --> 01:16:56.340
that seems absolutely right that it is.

01:16:56.340 --> 01:16:58.920
Though I would say one
thing which is that,

01:16:58.920 --> 01:17:01.363
I think there's a human way of doing this

01:17:01.363 --> 01:17:04.287
that is somewhat distinctive because...

01:17:07.650 --> 01:17:10.400
Because animals change, other animals

01:17:10.400 --> 01:17:12.568
change their beliefs too.

01:17:12.568 --> 01:17:15.730
But I don't think my
sheep engaged in kind of

01:17:15.730 --> 01:17:17.790
counterfactual reasoning.

01:17:17.790 --> 01:17:19.100
So I think that this capacity

01:17:19.100 --> 01:17:20.870
for kind of actual reasoning here,

01:17:20.870 --> 01:17:24.277
means that we're capable of a
kind of knowledge development

01:17:24.277 --> 01:17:28.710
that is very distinctive and
therefore especially important

01:17:28.710 --> 01:17:31.580
because it's one of the
reasons why we can do things

01:17:31.580 --> 01:17:33.690
cognitively that other organisms,

01:17:33.690 --> 01:17:35.689
as far as we know, can't.

01:17:35.689 --> 01:17:38.159
- [Lady] And just for what it's worth,

01:17:38.159 --> 01:17:42.953
we have historical
co-relationship between kids.

01:17:42.953 --> 01:17:47.953
Between how much they're
capable of (mumbles).

01:17:49.950 --> 01:17:50.990
- Good.

01:17:50.990 --> 01:17:54.593
And as you said they're
conceptually connected, yeah.

01:17:55.960 --> 01:17:58.043
Yes, I agree with that, um, thank you.

01:18:00.120 --> 01:18:01.290
Yes.

01:18:01.290 --> 01:18:03.955
- [Man] Just a brief observation about

01:18:03.955 --> 01:18:05.890
usefulness and context.

01:18:05.890 --> 01:18:07.270
I think this isn't the spirit of

01:18:07.270 --> 01:18:09.030
the way you're thinking about things,

01:18:09.030 --> 01:18:12.570
but to say that as if way
of thinking about things

01:18:12.570 --> 01:18:16.640
is view useful, that's
something that might make sense

01:18:16.640 --> 01:18:18.010
or might be a plausible thing to say

01:18:18.010 --> 01:18:20.170
in some context but not others.

01:18:20.170 --> 01:18:23.948
And a very natural way
of dividing up context

01:18:23.948 --> 01:18:27.064
for some of these purposes
is to is to contrast

01:18:27.064 --> 01:18:30.104
the deliberative standpoint with

01:18:30.104 --> 01:18:33.950
a retrospective or explanatory
or third personal standpoint.

01:18:33.950 --> 01:18:35.950
This is very natural in connection

01:18:35.950 --> 01:18:37.930
with this original Kantian idea

01:18:37.930 --> 01:18:42.074
that we act under the idea of freedom,

01:18:42.074 --> 01:18:45.450
sort of like when you're
moving forward in life,

01:18:45.450 --> 01:18:47.400
there's nothing you can really do

01:18:47.400 --> 01:18:49.890
with a thought that it's
all determined in advance,

01:18:49.890 --> 01:18:51.890
that's not gonna help you decide

01:18:51.890 --> 01:18:53.732
what to eat for breakfast, right?

01:18:53.732 --> 01:18:58.110
You've gotta make up your
mind and within that context

01:18:59.902 --> 01:19:02.320
there's in some way no alternative

01:19:02.320 --> 01:19:04.960
but to assume that it's up
to us what we're going to do.

01:19:04.960 --> 01:19:07.100
That that same assumption
when we look back

01:19:07.100 --> 01:19:08.960
at what people have done in the past maybe

01:19:08.960 --> 01:19:11.775
less ultimately, less useful--

01:19:11.775 --> 01:19:12.608
- Including ourselves.

01:19:12.608 --> 01:19:13.640
- [Man] Including ourselves, exactly.

01:19:13.640 --> 01:19:15.427
So I think that's a very...

01:19:15.427 --> 01:19:19.268
You were mostly talking about explanatory

01:19:19.268 --> 01:19:22.090
and interpretive context or were trying

01:19:22.090 --> 01:19:24.060
to predict and explain things but

01:19:24.060 --> 01:19:25.160
at least some of these notions

01:19:25.160 --> 01:19:27.090
and I think the same
is true of rationality,

01:19:27.090 --> 01:19:28.410
notions of reasons,

01:19:28.410 --> 01:19:31.180
they have some predictive significance.

01:19:31.180 --> 01:19:32.410
And certainly of some significance

01:19:32.410 --> 01:19:33.840
in the retrospective point of view

01:19:33.840 --> 01:19:38.020
but really, again, it's hard to know

01:19:38.020 --> 01:19:39.270
how you're gonna get through life

01:19:39.270 --> 01:19:42.345
without assuming that the
fact that a car is coming

01:19:42.345 --> 01:19:45.626
bearing down on you is a
reason to get out of the way.

01:19:45.626 --> 01:19:50.626
And that that idea has
tremendous significance

01:19:50.640 --> 01:19:52.090
in that deliberative context,

01:19:52.090 --> 01:19:54.370
which might be entirely independent

01:19:54.370 --> 01:19:58.310
from whether it's useful
in other concepts.

01:19:58.310 --> 01:20:00.070
Take that to be gristle
for your (mumbles).

01:20:00.070 --> 01:20:02.419
- No, no, I think that's very helpful.

01:20:02.419 --> 01:20:06.280
And the difficulty I think about

01:20:06.280 --> 01:20:08.960
the sort of useful for what question

01:20:08.960 --> 01:20:12.210
is that it can sometimes
be hard to articulate

01:20:12.210 --> 01:20:13.660
the for what.

01:20:13.660 --> 01:20:15.350
We do have some cases,

01:20:15.350 --> 01:20:18.941
the practical what am I doing question,

01:20:18.941 --> 01:20:21.296
that's one context as
we know how to sort of

01:20:21.296 --> 01:20:24.890
define in that rather crude way

01:20:24.890 --> 01:20:26.662
but still it's an important way.

01:20:26.662 --> 01:20:30.020
As I said I think it's a bit less clear

01:20:31.890 --> 01:20:35.800
what it is to say that it's useful

01:20:35.800 --> 01:20:39.510
for the purposes of
understanding to say something,

01:20:39.510 --> 01:20:42.300
but nevertheless I think I
want to say that sometimes.

01:20:42.300 --> 01:20:46.300
And then sometimes...

01:20:50.932 --> 01:20:53.660
Just to go back to the make-believe thing,

01:20:53.660 --> 01:20:55.768
as I said, adults do make-believe,

01:20:55.768 --> 01:20:58.333
that's what we're doing in the theater.

01:20:59.760 --> 01:21:04.760
We're responding as if
Juliet just killed herself

01:21:05.380 --> 01:21:09.830
because she discovered Romeo
dead on the thing beside her

01:21:09.830 --> 01:21:11.733
or is it the other way
around? I can't remember.

01:21:13.020 --> 01:21:14.750
And we're moved by that, as we would be

01:21:14.750 --> 01:21:18.490
if we came across such an event in reality

01:21:20.290 --> 01:21:22.833
but we're not confused
about what's going on.

01:21:25.377 --> 01:21:27.463
That means it's all Kendall Walton.

01:21:32.071 --> 01:21:34.404
For what, are we doing that?

01:21:37.405 --> 01:21:38.238
I don't know.

01:21:39.274 --> 01:21:41.490
I mean it's one of the
most important things

01:21:41.490 --> 01:21:43.040
that happens to me when
going to the theater,

01:21:43.040 --> 01:21:44.820
so it's not that I don't have any doubt

01:21:44.820 --> 01:21:46.810
that that for what is
an important for what,

01:21:46.810 --> 01:21:49.479
it's just that I don't know that there's

01:21:49.479 --> 01:21:53.390
an interesting way of
specifying what it is.

01:21:53.390 --> 01:21:55.100
And maybe there doesn't have to be

01:21:55.100 --> 01:21:57.970
an interesting one in the sense
of theoretically interesting

01:21:57.970 --> 01:22:00.500
maybe it's just one of the
things that human beings

01:22:00.500 --> 01:22:02.500
either do or don't get.

01:22:02.500 --> 01:22:05.857
So that it's like the funny,

01:22:05.857 --> 01:22:07.800
or the amusing.

01:22:07.800 --> 01:22:10.420
I don't know that one can
give an interesting account

01:22:10.420 --> 01:22:13.050
of the amusing but life
without it would be,

01:22:13.050 --> 01:22:15.469
at least for me, less interesting.

01:22:15.469 --> 01:22:17.077
Yes, less amusing (laughs).

01:22:18.565 --> 01:22:21.020
- [Campbell] We're trying to get one more.

01:22:21.020 --> 01:22:21.853
Yes please.

01:22:24.330 --> 01:22:25.570
- Hi.

01:22:25.570 --> 01:22:27.920
- There's an (clears throat) excuse me.

01:22:27.920 --> 01:22:32.110
There's an approach which
seems to me obviously promising

01:22:32.110 --> 01:22:34.980
and so I'm wondering if
you have thoughts about it

01:22:34.980 --> 01:22:36.294
or problems with it.

01:22:36.294 --> 01:22:38.720
When you talk about idealizations

01:22:38.720 --> 01:22:43.720
and wonder how can this
fictional thing be useful,

01:22:44.480 --> 01:22:46.915
in science and technology,

01:22:46.915 --> 01:22:50.550
there's the concept of approximations.

01:22:50.550 --> 01:22:53.991
And there're elaborate techniques

01:22:53.991 --> 01:22:58.991
for evaluating their
goodness and their utility

01:22:59.120 --> 01:23:00.983
for different purposes.

01:23:00.983 --> 01:23:05.360
Would that perhaps solve
some of your problems?

01:23:05.360 --> 01:23:07.860
- So it's an instance
of, thank you very much.

01:23:07.860 --> 01:23:11.320
It's an instance of the general question

01:23:11.320 --> 01:23:13.143
and I didn't say much about it in part

01:23:13.143 --> 01:23:15.780
because I haven't thought
too much about it,

01:23:15.780 --> 01:23:17.800
but also because I think it is as you say,

01:23:17.800 --> 01:23:22.160
a relatively well-developed
area of thinking about this.

01:23:22.160 --> 01:23:24.270
That is, this is one of the places where

01:23:24.270 --> 01:23:27.840
people already have the
idea that it can be useful

01:23:27.840 --> 01:23:30.480
to use a picture that's
strictly speaking false,

01:23:30.480 --> 01:23:34.016
because it gets you in a certain domain,

01:23:34.016 --> 01:23:37.761
approximately the right answer.

01:23:37.761 --> 01:23:40.560
I think that's a really
good answer to the question

01:23:40.560 --> 01:23:44.943
why you should use a certain
picture in a certain domain.

01:23:47.150 --> 01:23:51.893
But of course as was pretty
much explicit in what you said,

01:23:57.240 --> 01:23:59.170
being sort of approximately good enough

01:23:59.170 --> 01:24:04.023
is relative to a thing
you're trying to understand.

01:24:06.790 --> 01:24:10.360
I was once years ago, actually in company

01:24:10.360 --> 01:24:11.410
with Richard Braithwaite,

01:24:11.410 --> 01:24:14.140
listening to a theoretical physicist

01:24:14.140 --> 01:24:17.590
and he was talking about
the fundamental constants.

01:24:17.590 --> 01:24:19.329
And he went through a
bunch of mathematics,

01:24:19.329 --> 01:24:23.450
very much physicists mathematic,

01:24:23.450 --> 01:24:26.370
so lot of gestures here and there.

01:24:26.370 --> 01:24:30.847
And at the end he wrote down
122 or something, he said,

01:24:30.847 --> 01:24:32.397
"That's close enough to 12!"

01:24:33.464 --> 01:24:35.020
(audience laughs) which is
the number he was getting.

01:24:35.020 --> 01:24:37.580
Now, (audience laughing)
in a calculation where

01:24:37.580 --> 01:24:39.800
you know sometimes
you've been 10 to this 93

01:24:39.800 --> 01:24:41.590
and sometimes you've
been 10 to the minus 15,

01:24:41.590 --> 01:24:44.620
actually 12 is pretty close 120, right?

01:24:44.620 --> 01:24:46.490
But you need to know what the context is,

01:24:46.490 --> 01:24:50.453
to decide whether something
is approximately good enough.

01:24:51.359 --> 01:24:54.410
I think, again, this is well understood,

01:24:54.410 --> 01:24:56.550
I'm not telling you something that you

01:24:56.550 --> 01:24:57.810
or other people don't know.

01:24:57.810 --> 01:25:01.520
That's a relatively
well-developed area of thought

01:25:01.520 --> 01:25:02.993
about one particular kind.

01:25:04.400 --> 01:25:05.810
Well known not just by philosophers

01:25:05.810 --> 01:25:09.490
but by scientists themselves
'cause they need the notion

01:25:09.490 --> 01:25:11.300
of approximation in order to do this work

01:25:11.300 --> 01:25:13.000
and they need to be able to decide

01:25:14.034 --> 01:25:19.034
when to accept which
approximations for which purposes.

01:25:19.410 --> 01:25:22.202
But of course the point is
that you do need to specify

01:25:22.202 --> 01:25:25.400
what you're trying to do in
order to decide whether...

01:25:31.610 --> 01:25:33.850
Our theory of rational agency,

01:25:33.850 --> 01:25:36.020
very often predicts that someone will,

01:25:36.020 --> 01:25:37.713
I don't know, buy something.

01:25:38.810 --> 01:25:39.683
Then they don't.

01:25:41.201 --> 01:25:43.773
Now, but they buy something else.

01:25:44.840 --> 01:25:46.778
Is the theory approximately true

01:25:46.778 --> 01:25:48.623
because they bought something?

01:25:48.623 --> 01:25:49.588
(laughs) Well, that depends on

01:25:49.588 --> 01:25:52.170
whether what they bought is sort of

01:25:52.170 --> 01:25:53.820
like enough to the thing that you said

01:25:53.820 --> 01:25:56.040
they were going to buy I suppose.

01:25:56.040 --> 01:25:58.820
Or on whether alternatively,

01:25:58.820 --> 01:26:01.110
not treating it as an approximation,

01:26:01.110 --> 01:26:03.170
an explanation for why there's a deviation

01:26:03.170 --> 01:26:05.670
between what the rational thing was to do

01:26:05.670 --> 01:26:07.600
and what they actually did.

01:26:07.600 --> 01:26:11.380
They were distracted
by something and so on.

01:26:11.380 --> 01:26:14.620
But yeah, approximation, in
the book I'm writing about it.

01:26:14.620 --> 01:26:15.840
I'm not gonna talk much
about approximation,

01:26:15.840 --> 01:26:17.390
not because I don't think
it's really important,

01:26:17.390 --> 01:26:19.310
because it seems to me better understood

01:26:19.310 --> 01:26:20.900
than some of these other thing.

01:26:20.900 --> 01:26:23.490
But it's a really important
part of the subject.

01:26:23.490 --> 01:26:24.323
- [Campbell] That was a delightful

01:26:24.323 --> 01:26:26.739
and very stimulating
talk, thank you very much.

01:26:26.739 --> 01:26:31.739
- Thank you very much.
